(91,2025,20,103,'3','Spanish for Medical Professionals','Alyssa Selmer',1,'SPA',NULL,'Spanish for Medical ProfessionalsThis SPA 103 course is geared towards students who are interested in pursuing a career in medicine.  We will cover the same grammatical topics as our standard 103 courses, and will emphasize vocabulary related to the human body and medicine.  We will engage in role play situations as part of our practice in the field.  We will also discuss issues related to medical interpretation with a focus on relationships with patients and building empathy.  Fulfills same prerequisites and same degree/major requirements as other SPA 103 sections. Students who have already earned credit for SPA 103 may not also earn credit for the Spanish for Medical Professionals section of SPA 103.','SPA 102,SPA 102C','Language'),
(92,2025,25,119,'5','Calculus-Single Variable Part I','Melanie King',1,'MAT',NULL,'Differential and integral calculus of functions of one real variable and analytic geometry of two variables. This course emphasizes review of precalculus material and is appropriate for students who feel they need more time in order to succeed in calculus. Unless a departmental exception is granted, this course combination of MAT 119 and MAT 120 must be taken in consecutive terms. This course is not open to students who have completed MAT 121 or higher.','three and one-half years of high school mathematics, including trigonomotry','Mathematics'),
(93,2025,25,751,'Adjunct Fall','Percussion Instruments','Virginia Armstrong',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(94,2025,20,103,'3','Beginning Spanish III FEE1','Juana New Gavidia',1,'SPA',3750,'SPA 103 is the last course of a three-term sequence of beginning-level Spanish language at Cornell College. Students in this class will travel to Bolivia and get to know the language and the culture of this wonderful country. Bolivia is famous for its contrasting geographies, rich biodiversity, and culinary traditions. It is also a plurinational state and the country with the largest Indigenous population in the Americas. We will stay in the city of Sucre (designated by Unesco as a World Heritage Site), tour the countryside, the salt flats of Uyuni, the Indigenous market of Tarabuco, and travel to Potosí, once the most rich, cosmopolitan, and developed city in the Americas. Students will learn Spanish with native Bolivian teachers. They will stay in the homes of Bolivian families at walk distance from the school, located in the colonial center of Sucre. In the afternoon, students will have the opportunity to explore the city, visit historical settings, and participate in cultural activities.Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development.Total course cost: $3,750. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog.This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','SPA 102, SPA 102C','Language'),
