(98,2025,18,106,'6','Everyone\'s a Critic (W)','Scott Morris',1,'ENG',NULL,'Whether it’s the haughty pages of the New York Times, comedic TikTok stitches, or rambling IMDB forums, you’ll find opinions about art, fashion, and media everywhere. The best of these opinions, written by thoughtful and experienced critics like Roxane Gay or Zadie Smith, rise above mere review or content creation: Under the master critic’s guidance, a discussion of the latest video game, tech gadget, comedy special, or hit album becomes its own form of art exploring how these cultural artifacts affect and reflect real lives. In this class, we’ll read many exemplary critics who blend artful analysis with personal flair, and we’ll emulate them as we respond to the contemporary media and movements that are important to us. As we create these critiques, we’ll work across multiple genres -- from traditional review articles to cultural criticism essays to fanzines -- practicing the key skills of successful writers: drafting, revising, collaborating, more revising, and publishing. Students will write many drafts of smaller prompts preparing for a longer written essay. Major features of this class are its non-traditional labor-based grading--meant to encourage risk-taking in writing--and a peer workshop revision method. Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Humanities'),
(99,2025,25,207,'2','Human Systems Physiology & Anatomy I','Kristi Meyer',1,'BIO',NULL,'Part I in a two part series of a fundamental study of the complementarity of human anatomical structure and physiological function of the integumentary, endocrine, nervous, muscular, cardiovascular, respiratory, digestive, and renal systems.  Special emphasis on development of mechanistic understanding of organ system function and integrated physiological function across systems to promote homeostatic regulation in the human body. Inclusion of experiential learning through laboratory activities. Previously listed as KIN 207.','','Science'),
(100,2025,18,483,'2','Studio Art Seminar','Susannah Biondo-Gemmell',1,'ART',NULL,'This course is the seminar component of the senior studio art capstone experience.  Every studio art major is required to take this course during the senior year (unless permitted earlier).  This course will cover art theory, studio practice, and professional practice.  Art theory will be investigated through a series of seminal art historical readings.  Students will also be assigned a private or semi-private studio space in which they will begin developing their own studio art practice to culminate in a senior thesis exhibition at the end of the academic year.  This course will investigate professional pathways/careers/opportunities, resources/tools, and skills needed to continue in the field of art.  This will include visits with professional panels and necessary skill-building workshops (in areas such as resume building, artist statement construction, documentation of artwork through eportfolios/images, etc.).   The block will end with group studio visits to each artist’s studio to provide feedback on his/her current progress.','',''),
(101,2025,25,216,'4','Classical Mythology (in English)','Chris Hoklotubbe',1,'CLA',NULL,'Development of the myth, legend, and folklore of the ancient world, especially their place in ancient Greek and Roman culture, and their survival in the modern world.','','Humanities'),
(102,2025,25,771,'Adjunct Spring','Cello: String Instruments','James Ellis',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(103,2025,25,362,'7','Strategic Management Capstone Seminar','Tony Rose',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course is intended to introduce students to the basics of the how organizations are managed, with a special focus on the role played by a business firm’s strategy. Strategic management is concerned with how a firm sets its direction, chooses its business activities, and establishes and defends its position in a competitive market. This course will introduce you to concepts and tools that will help you to develop an understanding of how strategies are formed and managed, and how competitive advantage might be created and sustained.','ECB 110, ECB 151, ECB 328','Social Science'),
