(123,2025,25,105,'3','Marine Life & Environments','Andrew Walters',1,'GEO',NULL,'Previously titled GEO 105 \'Marine Science\'.An introduction to the global marine environment, with emphasis on sea floor dynamics, submarine topography and sediments, the nature and circulation of oceanic waters, coastal processes, marine biologic productivity, coral reefs and pollution, and exploitation of the oceans by humans.','','Science'),
(124,2025,25,151,'2','Financial Accounting','Huan Cai',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course provides guidance in how to use accounting reports for financial analysis.  The primary objective of this course is to understand and analyze financial statements including Balance Sheet, Income Statement, Statement of Cash Flows, and Statement of Retained Earnings. Objectives of financial accounting rather than bookkeeping techniques.','','Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(125,2025,25,101,'3','Macroeconomics','A\'amer Farooqi',1,'ECB',NULL,'Basic macroeconomic theory. Analytical evaluation of the determinants of national output, inflation, and unemployment. Examination of fiscal and monetary policies and issues in international trade and payments. Introduction of tools necessary to analyze economic models.','','Social Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(126,2025,25,101,'3','Sociological Thinking','Tori Barnes-Brus',1,'SOC',NULL,'Do you wonder why people do the things they do?  Why society works as it does?  Ever think the world is “unfair”?  Sociologists study people in the world, looking at patterns, at differences, at inequalities.  Thinking sociologically is like “entering a new and unfamiliar society--one in which things are no longer what they seem.”  It creates “culture shock without geographical displacement.”  This course requires us to look at society with a new perspective, to question our taken-for-granted assumptions, to investigate people\'s actions, and to explore the organization of society.  It provides a basis for being engaged citizens, thinking about social alternatives, and imagining possibilities for social justice. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(127,2025,25,382,'2','Counseling and Psychotherapy','Kris Robbins',1,'PSY',NULL,'What factors may lead some people to struggle with mental illness while others don’t?  What behaviors can we show as a therapist to make our clients feel heard and understood?  This course will explore theories of the causes of mental illness and will examine the most effective ways to treat these illnesses.  Students will practice counseling skills via role plays and will develop diagnosis and treatment plans based on client case studies.','PSY 243, PSY 244, PSY 245, PSY 256, PSY 265, PSY 274, PSY 276, PSY 277, PSY 278, PSY 279, PSY 280, PSY 282, PSY 283, PSY 292, PSY 200','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(128,2025,25,753,'Adjunct Spring','Lighting, Sound and Projection MOCK','Shawn Ketchum Johnson',0.25,'THE',NULL,'This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(129,2025,25,725,'Adjunct Fall','Pop/Contemporary Ensemble','Benjamin Laur',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'CCM (contemporary commercial music) performance ensemble. Students will learn songs together from the popular repertoire, including folk/country, rock, pop, and R&B, and rehearse and perform in groups. Some facility with voice or an instrument (keyboard, guitar, bass guitar, drums/percussion suggested) required. Placement by audition. Repeatable for credit.','',''),
(130,2025,18,106,'3','Writing International History (W)','Jonathon Dreeze',1,'HIS',NULL,'This is a first-year writing seminar course that will focus on creating the necessary reading, writing, and critical thinking skills students will need to succeed academically at Cornell, as well as professionally in their chosen career paths after graduation. The larger theme of the course will be international history. This course will examine some of the political, economic, and military relations between major world powers from the early 20th century to the breakup of the Soviet Union. Largely through the prism of writing, students will seek to understand the ways in which the Great Powers attempted to balance their national needs for economic and military security, with their desire for international prominence and stability. Coursework will consist of in-class discussion, shorter informal and formal writing assignments, as well as longer staged writing projects. Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Humanities'),
(131,2025,15,358,'8','Analytics Case Seminar','Santhi Hejeebu',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course applies the techniques of business analytics to a specific are of application, for example marketing analytics, health care analytics, sports analytics, etc. The course will involve a major case study with an actual organization. The specific orientation of the course will depend on the faculty instructor. ','ECB 121, ECB 353, ECB 354','Writing Encounter'),
(132,2025,25,122,'8','Calculus of Several Variables','Fabian Candelaria',1,'MAT',NULL,'Continuation of Calculus of a Single Variable, including further techniques of integration, vectors, and differential and integral calculus of several variables. ','MAT 120, MAT 121','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(133,2025,25,225,'7','General Physics I','Niloofar Kamran',1,'PHY',NULL,'Introduction to physics intended for physical science majors. Topics include Newton\'s laws of motion, concepts of work and energy, rotational motion, and conservation laws.','MAT 120, MAT 121','Science'),
(134,2025,25,115,'5','Beginning Electronic Music','Benjamin Laur',1,'MUS',NULL,'An introduction to creating electronic music using Digital Audio Workstations. Designed for a range of students from those with no prior musical training to aspiring professional musicians, this course will cover the basic principles of sound processing and MIDI, as well as compositional concepts and techniques for electronic music creation and beat making.','','Fine Arts'),
(135,2025,25,430,'6','Student Teaching III','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. Prerequisites: All 200- and 300-level Education courses and approval of the Education Department.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','EDU 420','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(136,2025,25,125,'4','The History of Dating','Tyler Carrington',1,'HIS',NULL,'Much has been written about the fusion of technology and dating over the last decade, and rightly so: dating websites, dating apps like Tinder and Hinge, and other digital dating services have made a tremendous impact on the way we think about romance in the twenty-first century. What is less often discussed is the origins of these dating innovations. Dating apps in fact have deep roots going back into the 1800s, and technological innovations far older than the smartphone or App Store have shaped the way people look for love and, crucially, conflicted with what different groups and cultures have considered appropriate and respectable. This course will explore the history of dating from the perspective of technology and its complicated relationship with slower-changing norms and mores. Our readings and material will focus on a variety of countries and contexts, from pre-WWI Germany to 1950s America; Cold War Europe to modern-day Tokyo; the 1700s to futuristic Black Mirror television. The goal is to emerge from the course not only with a sense of the long and wide history of dating but also with practice in considering the nuances of technological innovation and its interaction with human relationships.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(137,2025,17,348,'2','Theatre and the Arts in NYC FEE1','Scott Olinger',1,'THE',25,'The study of American art and culture, focusing particularly on theatrical performance, opera, and dance in NYC. Typically includes backstage tours, museum and gallery visits, and workshops/meals with local actors, designers, and other theatre artists. Students will attend and discuss approximately 14-18 performances of varying types, and reflect upon their overall experience.Location: New York City.Offered every third year.Total course cost: $4,150. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog.This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','THE 201','Off-Campus Course'),
(138,2025,20,270,'3','Electronic Instrumentation','Derin Sherman',1,'EGR',NULL,'Principles of electronics, signal processing, and computer interfacing needed to understand, configure, and troubleshoot modern electronic and computer-based research equipment. Transducers, operational amplifiers, test equipment, integrated circuits, data transmission, computerized data acquisition, and analog to digital conversion. Same course as CSC 270.','PHY 245, CSC 218','Writing Encounter'),
(139,2025,15,200,'1','Art & Community (SYS)','Susannah Biondo-Gemmell',1,'ART',NULL,'In this course, students will investigate the intersection of art and the community through a series of hands-on studio art projects. What does community mean in the context of visual art? How have artists used art as a mechanism for social change? How can artists create meaningful connections with the community and give back at both local and global levels? We will learn how artists have responded to historical events and social issues that impact communities. Students will consider both historical and contemporary public art. Students will learn hands-on technical art processes that will be used for larger community engaged artworks and projects. Yes, students will be MAKING art. Major studio projects will be both collaborative and individual in nature. The focus of this course is to consider ways in which the mission of art can shift from a personal endeavor to community connection and outreach. Students will gain skills in the visual arts, while intersecting with and contributing to the broader community. [SA] Only open to sophomores.','','Sophomore Year Seminar, SYS, Fine Arts'),
(140,2025,25,101,'7','Macroeconomics','A\'amer Farooqi',1,'ECB',NULL,'Basic macroeconomic theory. Analytical evaluation of the determinants of national output, inflation, and unemployment. Examination of fiscal and monetary policies and issues in international trade and payments. Introduction of tools necessary to analyze economic models.','','Social Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(141,2025,24,201,'5','Statistical Methods I','Tyler George',1,'STA',NULL,'Elementary study of the science of data. Data collection, descriptive statistics, estimation, and hypothesis testing as applied to one- and two-variable problems.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(142,2025,5,485,'2','Problems','Nicole Green',1,'BMB',NULL,'Investigation of a biological problem, including a review of the literature, collection and interpretation of data, and writing of a research report. May be repeated once for credit. Intended for seniors or advanced juniors, this is a capstone experience for Biology and BMB majors. Arrangements must be made with the instructor before registering. May be repeated once for credit.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation for Ingenuity in Action. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','Nicole Green','Writing Encounter'),
(143,2025,25,715,'Adjunct Fall','The Rehearsal Process SISTERS','Patrick DuLaney',0.25,'THE',NULL,'Participation in rehearsal process as a performer or on production team for a minimum of six weeks.','',''),
(144,2025,18,306,'8','Secondary Social Science Methods','Jill Heinrich',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course introduces students to methods and strategies for teaching social studies and history at the secondary level. In the course students will be introduced to the historical and theoretical foundations of teaching social sciences, as well as to general issues involved in\r\nplanning and organizing a social studies curriculum. These include primary source-based history instruction; methods of historical production (e.g., films, graphic histories, documentaries); curriculum development; aligning instruction with standards; technology and social studies teaching; and assignment design and evaluation.  This course is conducted at the practicum site. Transportation to and from the practicum site is the responsibility of the student. Course is graded Credit/No Credit.','EDU 301, EDU 328','Credit/No Credit'),
(145,2025,200,104,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning Research','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Global Connections experiences are opportunities for students to broaden their perspective and improving their intercultural literacy through engaging with people from a culture other than their own culture or immersing themselves in a culture different from their own.  Global Connections experiences should also deepen students’ understanding of the interconnectedness of the world and the range of political, social, cultural, and economic issues affecting cultures and interactions around the world.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(146,2025,25,363,'1','Feminist Art','Chris Penn-Goetsch',1,'ART',NULL,'Investigation of the feminist art movement of the 1970s to the present, as well as contemporary artwork by women artists. Readings and lectures focus on feminist approaches to gender, ethnicity, class, sexual orientation, and colonialism. This course also counts toward the GSS major. Alternate years. No alternative grade option. [AH]','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, GSS 171','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive, Writing Encounter'),
(147,2025,25,798,'Adjunct Spring','Half Recital','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'25 minutes of music. Required of Music Performance majors. Available to any student with approval of the Department. No alternative grade option. A pre-recital hearing is required. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Ingenuity in Action, Creative Expression'),
(148,2025,25,320,'3','Sociology of the Environment','Mary Olson',1,'SOC',NULL,'The course will explore the interactions of human social systems with ecosystems, considering the ways in which people, other animals, plants, land, water, and air are closely interconnected.  It will investigate how human consumption and production, along with technology, population, health, and inequalities are interwoven with environmental conditions.  It will also study how the cultures, ideas, moral values and social experiences of different human groups, from modern Americans to indigenous populations, influence the way people think about and act toward the environment.  Finally, it will contemplate a number of ways in which people might act, both individually and collectively, to bring about a more ecological society. Alternate years.This course may count toward the SOC, CPH, and ENV major.','SOC 101, ANT 101, RES 123','Social Science'),
(149,2025,18,104,'5','Studio Art Basics 3D','Mark Baker',1,'ART',60,'Introductory-level studio art course exploring art elements, concepts, and history. Three versions are offered on a rotating basis: 2-D, 3-D, and Photo Imaging. Students are not allowed to repeat this course even if the medium is different. No alternative grade option.[SA]This course has an additional materials fee of $60 per student.','','Fine Arts'),
(150,2025,25,762,'Adjunct Fall','Piano','James Martin',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(151,2025,25,334,'1','Animal Behavior','Rebecca Richtsmeier-Ross, Josh Otten',1,'BIO',NULL,'Evolution, development, causation, and function of behavior with emphasis on the origins and adaptive function of behaviors of vertebrates and invertebrates. This course includes one overnight field trip which requires an additional fee for lodging and facility rental. Other field trips may extend beyond normal class hours.Offered subject to availability of staff.','BIO 221, BIO 211','Science'),
(152,2025,25,212,'4','Mineralogy','Emily Walsh',1,'GEO',NULL,'An introduction to the physical, chemical, and structural properties of minerals. Will explore the significance of minerals across many fields, and will provide a hands-on approach, including growing minerals and using mineral hand-samples, crystal form models, atomic structure models, and polarizing microscopes to uncover even the subtlest properties of minerals.','GEO 105, GEO 106, GEO 107, GEO 111, GEO 122, GEO 125, GEO 130, GEO 160','Science, Writing Encounter'),
(153,2025,18,310,'3','Theoretical Foundations of Elem Sch Math','Corrine Neville',1,'INT',NULL,'This course is designed for Elementary Education majors. This course will focus on understanding elementary mathematical concepts and processes taught in the elementary (K-8) curriculum. Noted are the fundamental mathematical concepts most applicable for teaching at the elementary level: number and operations, algebra, geometry, data analysis and probability. This course requires an in-person practicum experience at the school. Student will need to provide their own transportation.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240',NULL),
(154,2025,25,366,'8','Topics: Philosophy of Emotions','Megan Altman',1,'PHI',NULL,'More now than ever, philosophers working in a wide variety of areas are interested in emotion. Discussion of emotion figures prominently in moral psychology, action theory, aesthetics, and even in some strains of philosophy of mind and epistemology. But what exactly are emotions? What exactly would we be missing out on if we did not experience them? In this course, we will consider a variety of (mostly) contemporary philosophical responses to these questions. We will begin by examining the most prominent theories about the composition of emotions: are they feelings? Judgments? Perceptions? Then, we will move on to questions about the significance of emotions for human life. We will consider how emotions enable, sustain, or interfere with our capacities as knowers and as moral agents. We will conclude by considering some special topics.','PHI','Humanities'),
(155,2025,25,365,'1','Literature and Cinema','Juana New Gavidia',1,'ENG',NULL,'Investigating some of the multi-faceted connections between literature and film, this course may focus on a topic such as the investigation of transatlantic avant-garde film and the \"little magazines\" or film societies and literary coteries of the early twentieth century. See Topics Courses for expanded current course description. Alternate years.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, ENG 201, ENG 202, ENG 215, ENG 225','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(156,2025,15,483,'1','Senior Seminar','Steven Neese',1,'PSY',NULL,'This is the capstone course for Psychology and Behavioral Neuroscience students majoring in Behavioral Neuroscience or Psychological Sciences.  Students will co-lead group discussions on current issues within the field of Psychology.  Students will complete a comprehensive scientific research review paper on a topic related to their professional interests.  Students will reflect upon their professional aspirations and will prepare career-related materials including resumes, vitaes, cover letters, and personal statements. No alternative grade option.','PSY 392',''),
(157,2025,20,102,'7','Beginning Spanish II','Michael Mosier',1,'SPA',NULL,'<p>Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development. </p>','SPA 101, SPA 101C','Language'),
(158,2025,25,511,'Adjunct Fall','Extended Research in Geology','Rhawn Denniston',0.25,'GEO',NULL,'Two semesters to be taken in conjunction with capstone project, GEO 485. Extended reading during the first semester and writing of a capstone research proposal. Extended writing with construction and delivery of a public presentation of the capstone research results during the second semester. Permission of Instructor.','GEO 485',NULL),
(159,2025,25,351,'5','The Age of Revolution in America','Phil Lucas',1,'HIS',NULL,'The causes of the American Revolution, the writing and the implementation of the Constitution, and the War of 1812. No alternative grade option.','Junior Standing','Humanities'),
(160,2025,25,215,'6','Psychology of Sport','Christi Johnson',1,'KIN',NULL,'Theory and issues related to psychological aspects of competitive sport contexts. Personality and sport, attentional control, anxiety and performance, motivation and attributions, aggression in sport, and team cohesion. Intervention strategies for performance enhancement.','','Social Science, Writing Encounter'),
(161,2025,20,200,'1','Documentary Filmmaking (SYS)','Scott Olinger',1,'THE',NULL,'Explore a societal issue through the lens of documentary film. Students will work together in small groups to identify an issue, then plan, film and edit a short documentary film, all while studying the history of the genre. Experience with non-linear editing is useful, but not required. Phone cameras required.Only open to sophomores.','','Sophomore Year Seminar (SYS), Fine Arts'),
(162,2025,22,327,'4','Organic Chemistry Laboratory','Charley Liberko, Andrea Dunn, Harmeet Bhoday',1,'CHE',NULL,'Practical laboratory aspects of organic chemistry. Isolation and purification of substances; one-step transformations of substances; and, possibly, synthesis projects.','CHE 326','Science, Writing Encounter'),
(163,2025,18,265,'4','Improvisation','Patrick DuLaney',1,'THE',NULL,'Students taking this course will be given a basic overview and practice of long-form improvisation.  Students will be improvising in this class from day one.  In addition to daily practice, students will gain an understanding and appreciation of the history and culture of Improvisation.  Each week of this class will culminate in a public performance. Possible field trip to Chicago.','THE 115','Fine Arts'),
(164,2025,25,353,'1','Philosophy of Law','Genevieve Migely',1,'PHI',NULL,'Inquiry into the foundation and nature of law, and its relation to morality and society through both classical and contemporary legal theories. Specific issues covered include the notions of the scope and limits of individual liberty, the concept  and workings of legal justice, the role of legal responsibility, and the purpose of punishment through the analysis of legal cases and judicial interpretation. In discussing these topics, issues regarding how gender and race play a role in legal practice will also be addressed. Prerequisite: sophomore standing. Alternate years.','sophomore standing','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(165,2025,25,101,'2','Sociological Thinking','Mary Olson',1,'SOC',NULL,'Do you wonder why people do the things they do?  Why society works as it does?  Ever think the world is “unfair”?  Sociologists study people in the world, looking at patterns, at differences, at inequalities.  Thinking sociologically is like “entering a new and unfamiliar society--one in which things are no longer what they seem.”  It creates “culture shock without geographical displacement.”  This course requires us to look at society with a new perspective, to question our taken-for-granted assumptions, to investigate people\'s actions, and to explore the organization of society.  It provides a basis for being engaged citizens, thinking about social alternatives, and imagining possibilities for social justice. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(166,2025,18,200,'1','Science and Communication (SYS)','Nicole Green',1,'BIO',NULL,'In this course, students will address the need for better scientific communication with the public and investigate the importance of conveying accurate and accessible scientific information. How does the public engage with science? How does scientific information make its way from the lab into the coffee shops of our local communities, into our high school textbooks, or even the latest science fiction television series? What is the role and the responsibility of academic scientists in distributing scientific knowledge to the average citizen? How do artists and creators intersect with scientists to accomplish these goals? To learn communication strategies, we will use examples of effective science communication from popular scientific journalists, podcasts, art and museum exhibits, and science fiction television/film. We will explore the relationship between science and the public and actively participate in improving scientific engagement in our local community of Mount Vernon. Students will select a scientific topic, identify a target audience, and design a communication initiative using the skills gained throughout the course. Students from all academic backgrounds will be able to apply their skills–interdisciplinary approaches are strongly encouraged in developing community science engagement projects. Only open to sophomores.','','Sophomore Year Seminar (SYS), Science'),
(167,2025,15,223,'4','Utilitarian Ceramics','Susannah Biondo-Gemmell',1,'ART',90,'What is the “language” of pottery and how does it differ from sculpture? What details must artists consider as they create objects for the purpose of utility? In this course, students will use clay to explore pottery forms and the role of functionality today. Students will learn both wheel-throwing and hand-building techniques in order to create utilitarian ceramic objects. Both historical and contemporary pottery will be explored through studio projects, art historical readings/presentations, and individual research. Students will be involved in every step of the ceramic process from mixing clay, forming and glazing functional works of art, and loading/firing kilns. No alternative grade option. This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $90 per student.','ART 103, ART 104, ART 200, ART 115','Fine Arts'),
(168,2025,12,265,'1','The Alps: Culture, Econ, Ecology FEE1','Tyler Carrington',1,'GER',25,'The Alps loom large over the European continent, quite literally dwarfing the many cities and villages that make up western Europe, to say nothing of the comparatively tiny humans who trek up these mountains by the millions each year. But this famed mountain range also figures centrally in the European imagination and in fact coheres an entire region all its own. Indeed, the Alpine region is more cohesive and uniform than we might think, especially since it spans at least six different countries. Interestingly, culture, economy, and ecology in the Alps is remarkably consistent, and Alpine “tradition” and “innovation” are fascinating windows into the dynamics of this fabled region.This course is designed to make the myth of the German-speaking Alps real, meaningful, and unforgettable. Our course will begin in Switzerland with a hands-on exploration of Alpine artisanry and industry (from cheese-making to woodcutting and everything in between), augmented with some breathtaking climbs, cogwheel mountain trains, and practice learning to play the Alpine horn. From there we will pivot to Tyrol, the historic Alpine region spanning southern Germany, central Austria, and northern Italy. To investigate Tyrol, we will go first to Innsbruck (Austria) and, among other things, meet with the Austrian Alpine Society, hike the Austrian Alps, and descend into a historic silver mine. Then we will head south to Bozen (Italy), which affords us easy access to “Dorf Tirol,” the castle and land of the ruling family and namesake of this still very German-speaking (though now, since 1917, nominally Italian) region. We will also immerse ourselves in Tyrolean culture, for example by taking yodeling lessons there and practicing our new skills while hiking. Our time in Bozen will also be punctuated by meetings and workshops with several departments at the University of Bozen, including Mountain Environmental Sciences; Tourism, Sport, and Event Management; and Enogastronomy.Students will return from this off-campus course with concrete, specific knowledge of how and why Alpine life functions, then and now, and a collection of experiences and visual memories that will nourish a love of the Alps for a lifetime to come.A note on the physical, athletic requirements of this course:This course will include numerous semi-serious hiking excursions, to say nothing of a lot of walking in hilly places at elevation. We will not do any technical climbing or hiking in snow or otherwise dangerous locations, and we will certainly not be in a race or in a hurry; but traversing trails in the Alps requires a different kind of physicality and endurance than your typical class (even your typical off-campus class). Students should think carefully and honestly about whether they will be able to participate meaningfully in class in these environments and activities. Enrolled students should also do some pre-conditioning over the summer to prepare for hiking and walking at elevation (ca. 3000 m above sea level).Required Supplies (purchased on your own)-one pair hiking sticks (e.g. Leki trekking poles @ $90)-hiking boots-international cell phone data plan','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(169,2025,99,715,'Adjunct Spring','Orchestra','Andrew Gentzsch',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(170,2025,99,717,'Adjunct Spring','Chamber Singers','Christopher Nakielski',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(171,2025,18,106,'5','The Beatles: Music, Critics & Culture(W)','Jama Stilwell',1,'MUS',NULL,'This course will be primarily devoted to developing your skills as a writer.  In addition, woven throughout all of our writing, reading, and discussion, will be an examination of the music of the Beatles!  The course will move chronologically, stopping along the way to consider six of the most ground-breaking Beatles albums: A Hard Day’s Night (1964), Rubber Soul (1965), Revolver (1966), Sgt. Pepper’s Lonely Hearts Club Band (1967), The Beatles (The “White Album,” 1968), and Abbey Road (1969).  You will spend a considerable amount of time listening to music, and writing about what you hear.  You will also be required to read, discuss, and write based on the following topics: the Beatles’ influences from the blues & early rock ‘n roll; their methods of constructing albums & songs; their melding of diverse stylistic influences; their interaction with the culture & politics of their time; and responses to their music from audiences & critics.  No previous musical background is required!  Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Humanities'),
(172,2025,18,319,'2','Children\'s Literature','Madison Parker',1,'EDU',NULL,'Comparative study of literary texts for children, including instructional planning, the teaching of reading, the use of literature with elementary students, and student assessment. Thirty hours of observation-practicum in the schools. Students must provide their own transportation. This course must be taken PRIOR to student teaching. No alternative grade option. Students doing online learning are not eligible to take this course.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240','Writing Encounter'),
(173,2025,25,732,'Adjunct Spring','Trumpet: Brass Instruments','Desmond Cervantez',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(174,2025,25,256,'8','Topics: Stress Management','Christi Johnson',1,'KIN',NULL,'This course will explore the personal, social, and cultural dynamics of thriving, grit, resilience, mental toughness, and stress.  The class will survey the definitions and applications of these topics.  Additionally, students will explore ways in which each of the course topics (thriving, grit, resilience, mental toughness, stress) are culturally constructed and reflect dominant ideologies of privilege and power.   Students should expect to explore their personal patterns of stress and stress management, build a repertoire of stress management techniques, and critique wellness cultures that promote grit, resilience, and mental toughness without deep considerations of power and privilege.','',''),
(175,2025,25,361,'5','Cognitive Neuroscience','Steven Neese',1,'PSY',NULL,'A critical examination of memory and thought processes. Topics are likely to include: object recognition, attention, concept formation, memory systems, visual imagery, problem solving, judgment, language, and individual differences in cognition related to age, gender, and culture. Laboratory sessions will give students first-hand experiences with the phenomena covered in the class.','PSY 161, PSY 243, PSY 244, PSY 255, PSY 256, PSY 257, PSY 258, PSY 259, PSY 260, PSY 261, PSY 262, PSY 263, PSY 264, PSY 265, PSY 274, PSY 276, PSY 277, PSY 278, PSY 279, PSY 282, PSY 283, PSY 292, PSY 200','Social Science'),
(176,2025,25,511,'Adjunct Fall','Latin Reading Group','John Gruber-Miller',0.25,'LAT',NULL,'Maintenance of Latin language skills through reading a variety of Latin authors. Texts selected in consultation with the participating students. Course meets once a week for a semester.','LAT 102',NULL),
(177,2025,25,110,'4','Music Theory I','Jama Stilwell',1,'MUS',NULL,'Fundamentals of music: harmony, melody, rhythm, scales, and forms; with a concentration on the common-practice period, 1600-1900 (with some twentieth century music). Application of these topics to analysis, writing, listening, sight-singing, and an introduction to music literature.','MUS 101','Fine Arts'),
(178,2025,18,317,'4','Advanced Poetry Writing','Glenn Freeman',1,'ENG',NULL,'Advanced course in writing poetry. Students will study techniques, share work, and offer critiques. The course will also include the study of published poetry. Additional topics will include publication options, manuscript submission procedures, and resources for writers. May be repeated once for credit. Alternate years.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','ENG 215','Fine Arts, Writing Intensive'),
(179,2025,150,700,'8','Vacation','Registrar Staff',0,'VAC',NULL,'Vacation blocks are open to seniors who are on track to complete 31 credits by block 8 of their senior year.  Non seniors must petition for permission to take fewer than 4 blocks per semester. If the student is on track to have 31 credits by the end of their senior year, the petition will be approved and the student will be registered for a vacation block. Otherwise, the student must explain in the petition how they will make up the missed credit.','',''),
(180,2025,200,101,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Academic research experiences are opportunities for students to develop their understanding of professional methods and fields of study appropriate to a chosen discipline or proposed research question. The value of research for undergraduate students lies both in the intellectual development of the student and in the potential discovery of previously unknown information. Academic research experiences should therefore emphasize the development of disciplinary research skills and methodology; they should be substantial (in breadth, scope, maturity, and effort involved); and they should encourage students to engage with the planning, execution, and presentation of their research efforts.  In addition, sharing the results of one’s research is an important part of the research process, which calls upon the researcher to participate in a community of scholars. Research experiences therefore should be presented or published in some form.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(181,2025,25,311,'6','Systems Software','Ajit Chavan',1,'CSC',NULL,'Process scheduling and synchronization, interprocess communication, allocation of memory and disk space. Creation and use of software, libraries, tools, and methods for the production of efficient, reliable software. Alternate years','CSC 144, CSC 218, CSC 301',NULL),
(182,2025,18,215,'2','Introduction to Creative Writing','Glenn Freeman',1,'ENG',NULL,'Beginning course in creative writing and an introductory course to the English major. Students will explore a myriad of writing techniques and approaches to writing in a variety of genres. Students will write, share work, and offer critiques. The course also includes the study of published authors as models for student writing, as literary historical context for artistic creation, and for the study of creative theory. Students will learn to analyze texts from a writer’s perspective, which they will apply to their own writing and to the study of literature in the major.Required for English Major concentrators in Creative Writing.','','Fine Arts, Writing Encounter'),
(183,2025,25,323,'7','Shakespeare, Gender, Power','Katy Stavreva',1,'ENG',NULL,'Immersion into the plays of William Shakespeare with a focus on the performance of gender and power, and their relationship to identity- and political construction and disruption. Students will analyze comedies, tragedies, and hybrid-genre plays, attending to historical articulations of gender and power, and relating them to contemporary experiences. Assignments include scene studies and engaged critical and theoretical inquiry through presentations, projects, and papers. The class can function as a Research Seminar fulfilling the capstone requirement for the Literature and Society, and the Multimedia and Digital Writing concentrations of the English major.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, ENG 201, ENG 202, ENG 215, ENG 225','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(184,2025,25,308,'6','Vocal Pedagogy','Christopher Nakielski',1,'MUS',NULL,'Historical and pedagogical development of the art of singing and a study of the physiology of the singing process. Emphasis on teaching techniques and care of the voice. Required of all students majoring in voice. Open to other vocalists with the permission of instructor. Alternate years. No alternate grade option. L. HEARNE','Sophomore standing',''),
(185,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Spring','Flute: Woodwind Instruments','Victoria Bishop',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
