(210,2025,25,245,'1','Lifespan Development','Katelyn Pitcher',1,'PSY',NULL,'Investigation of the major subfields of psychology from a developmental perspective: cognition, emotion, motivation, personality/self, biological systems (brain/nervous system, endocrine), social relationships (peers and family). Includes discussions of research methods particular to lifespan research, genetic-environment interactions, prenatal development, and dying/bereavement.','','Social Science'),
(211,2025,25,121,'2','Data Visualization','Santhi Hejeebu',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course enables students to see stories in numbers. Students will work with business and economic data, students will identify central tendencies and patterns of dispersions. They will learn methods of exploring data and effectively communicating insights through appropriate graphical presentation.','','Social Science, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(212,2025,25,515,'Adjunct Spring','Volunteer Income Tax Assistance Prog (2)','Santhi Hejeebu, Huan Cai',0.25,'ECB',NULL,'Volunteer Income Tax Assistance (VITA) is a national IRS sponsored program that provides free preparation of federal and state tax returns for households with income less than $60,000. Students in this course are expected to have finished all the training sessions from the prerequisite course Volunteer Income Tax Assistance (VITA) Program (1). During the tax season (during late January to early April), students will volunteer at VITA under the supervision of a site coordinator to help complete and file tax returns for those who can’t afford professional tax preparation services. Students select volunteering time slots of approximately 3 hours per week for the ten-week tax season. Time slots are available in the evenings. The total time commitment to receive credit is approximately 30 hours. This course may be repeated for credit.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action categroy, Civic Engagement. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','Volunteer Income Tax Assistance (VITA) Program (1)','Ingenuity in Action categroy, Civic Engagement'),
(213,2025,25,732,'Adjunct Fall','French Horn: Brass Instruments','Peter Kortenkamp',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(214,2025,20,101,'5','Beginning Spanish I','Alyssa Selmer',1,'SPA',NULL,'Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development.','','Language'),
(215,2025,18,318,'1','Methods-Elementary Lang Arts & Reading','Corrine Neville',1,'EDU',NULL,'Current elementary school methods in the teaching of reading, instructional planning, language acquisition, student assessment, and teaching materials in the field of elementary language arts and reading. Reading Recovery, Title I, and other literacy support programs are addressed. Thirty hours of observation-practicum in the schools. Students must provide their own transportation. This course must be taken PRIOR to student teaching. No alternative grade option. This course requires an in-person practicum experience at the school. Students doing online learning are not eligible to take this course.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240',''),
(216,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Fall','Flute: Woodwind Instruments','Victoria Bishop',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(217,2025,25,110,'3','Introduction to Management','Tony Rose',1,'ECB',NULL,'Introduction to Management examines the theory, techniques, and applications of management systems. Planning, organizing, leading, and controlling are issues addressed. It includes a detailed study of how firms determine their main objectives, plan their strategies, organize, motivate, and lead their employees to achieve those goals as well as control their operations to evaluate and correct their actions. Specific topics include environmental influences, organization design and structure, motivation, leadership, ethics, innovation, total quality management, etc. This course will help you understand and analyze how managers can formulate and implement strategies effectively, leverage values, build an engaging and motivating workplace, and manage risk and ambiguity.','','Social Science'),
(218,2025,25,321,'8','Computer Graphics','Leon Tabak',1,'CSC',NULL,'Introduction to the concepts and algorithms of computer graphics. Architecture of display systems, 2D and 3D geometry and algorithms, viewing transformations, interactive techniques, color concepts. Alternate years. ','CSC 301',NULL),
(219,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Fall','Oboe: Woodwind Instruments','Lisa Ryoo',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
