(224,2025,25,710,'Adjunct Fall','Advanced Jazz Improvisation','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'A continuation of MUS 215 Jazz Improvisation. Study and discussion of the various approaches to jazz improvisation. Focus will be on chord/scale relationships, advanced harmonic substitutions, stylistic considerations, solo analysis, and relationships between harmony, melody, and structure. Students will also begin learning important pieces in the basic jazz repertoire. May be repeated for credit. No alternate grade option.','',''),
(225,2025,20,111,'1','How Do We Know What We Know? FYS','Melanie King',1,'INT',NULL,'This common first year seminar explores how we know what we know and the various ways and conventions by which we communicate knowledge. For example, how do we take in and evaluate information? How do our brains make deliberate and/or rapid decisions? How does our knowledge both individually and societally change over time? What does it mean to know something? How do we consider perspectives different from our own? Learning requires raising questions that stem from reasoning, curiosity, and empathy. Through questioning, we become informed citizens and scholars. Through careful reading, creative and critical thinking, speaking and writing, we will engage with a variety of texts from many genres and disciplinary perspectives. Your instructor will serve as a guide along this path by encouraging you to consider different perspectives on and ways of knowing as you start to identify areas for your own growth as a college student.','',''),
(226,2025,25,122,'5','Climate Change','Rhawn Denniston',1,'GEO',NULL,'An examination of changes in Earth\'s climate with particular focus on the last 20,000 years. Topics include greenhouse and icehouse worlds, climate reconstruction techniques, and factors driving climate change. Offered as a Writing Requirement (W) course in alternate years.','','Science'),
(227,2025,200,101,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Academic research experiences are opportunities for students to develop their understanding of professional methods and fields of study appropriate to a chosen discipline or proposed research question. The value of research for undergraduate students lies both in the intellectual development of the student and in the potential discovery of previously unknown information. Academic research experiences should therefore emphasize the development of disciplinary research skills and methodology; they should be substantial (in breadth, scope, maturity, and effort involved); and they should encourage students to engage with the planning, execution, and presentation of their research efforts.  In addition, sharing the results of one’s research is an important part of the research process, which calls upon the researcher to participate in a community of scholars. Research experiences therefore should be presented or published in some form.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(228,2025,15,261,'7','Topics: Film Production','Scott Olinger',1,'THE',NULL,'Introduction to the process of making films, including storyboarding, shot composition, basic camera operation, camera movement, and the non-linear editing process. Will work in conjunction with THE 331 Acting for the Camera.','THE 331','Fine Arts'),
(229,2025,200,103,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning Off Campus Study','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Creative Expression experiences are opportunities for students to explore their creative potential and develop as artists. Activities in this category are focused on the conceptualization and execution of creative work. These experiences should emphasize exploring the student’s creative process and aesthetic choices. In addition, sharing one\'s work is an important part of the creative process, which calls upon the artist to participate in a community of other artists. Creative work therefore should be presented, published, performed, or exhibited in some form.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(230,2025,25,340,'2','Econometrics','Todd Knoop',1,'ECB',NULL,'Introduction to the use of statistics in economics and business, employing economic theory and real-world data in order to predict future demand for a product and to forecast levels of inflation and unemployment. Statistical methods include cross-section and time series analysis, and single and multivariate regression. Alternate years.','ECB 101, ECB 102, STA 201, STA 348','Writing Encounter'),
(231,2025,15,200,'1','His/Impact Photography (SYS)','Alex McKenzie',1,'ART',75,'This course surveys the history of photography and its continuing social and cultural impact. Students will gain functional camera and photo editing skills. Course activities include a balance between lectures, discussions, and studio projects. Only open to sophomores. This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $75 per student.','','Sophomore Year Seminar, Fine Arts'),
(232,2025,20,103,'8','Beginning French III','Rebecca Wines',1,'FRE',NULL,'FRE 101- FRE 103 develop students’ linguistic and cultural proficiency. Coursework covers speaking, listening, reading and writing in French. The French language will be used to communicate during 90% or more of class time by both the instructor and students. Successful completion of the beginning-level language course sequence prepares students to function in a variety of authentic communicative situations within a French speaking context and to become life-long language learners. All French language classes, from the beginning to the advanced level, also develop students’ awareness and understanding of cultural phenomena in the Francophone world. In French 103, students build on their cultural and linguistic proficiency in French through exercises in speaking, writing, listening and reading. Students learn how to express their future plans and career interests in French. They also learn about the French educational system and engage with authentic French media.','FRE 102','Language'),
(233,2025,25,210,'4','Warfare and Society in Modern Times','Jonathon Dreeze',1,'HIS',NULL,'This course will examine various components of modern military history, ranging from the 18th century through to the 21st century. While the specific conflagrations in each course will vary, we will explore such conflicts as the Napoleonic Wars, the American Civil War, the World Wars, the Korean War, the Vietnam War, and the other conflicts from the larger Cold War. Students will examine some of the traditional aspects of military history, such as tactics, weapons, and battles, but also examine the impact of broader themes in military history, such as social, ideological, gender, and ethnic aspects. One of the major themes of this course will be the plight of the individual – the individual as a soldier or the individual as a civilian – during wartime in various conflicts and eras in history. This course will also focus on the larger role that warfare has played in the course of history, specifically war’s ability to accelerate social, political, ideological, and technological change. No alternate grade option.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive, Writing Encounter'),
(234,2025,25,205,'8','Historical Foundations of Education','Sarah Doyle',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course explores the historical, sociological, and philosophical foundations of education. The class will draw upon the broad, theoretical issues of education through a variety of written and discussion-based activities. Particular attention is paid to curriculum theory, the civic and democratic mission of the common schools movement, Dewey and the Progressive Era of schooling, and the current social context of schools. Students are encouraged to critically analyze the purpose of schooling and to further develop their own philosophies of education through reflection and dialogue. No alternative grade option.Not open to juniors and seniors without the permission of instructor.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(235,2025,25,245,'4','Reel History: African Americans and Film','Catherine Stewart',1,'HIS',NULL,'This course examines how Black Americans have historically been represented in American film from the early 20th century through the first part of the 21st century. We will explore how Hollywood has depicted Black Americans, and race relations in the U.S., as well as how independent Black filmmakers such as Oscar Micheaux, Julie Dash, Spike Lee, Ava DuVernay, and others have sought to revise and critique white constructions of blackness. We will investigate how African American filmmakers, actors, and actresses have dealt with the contradictions of a film industry that has historically marginalized their contributions even as it has contributed to the proliferation of images of blackness, shaping public perceptions of American race relations. From the earliest beginnings of American cinema, Black directors, actors and actresses, musicians, dancers, film critics, and audiences have fought for inclusion and equal representation—on film, behind the camera, in the Hollywood community, and as filmgoers. An independent Black cinema emerged and evolved with its own aesthetic and film criticism. We will view a number of films from different eras and genres, including the so-called “race pictures” of Oscar Micheaux, Hollywood Black-cast musicals, social “problem” dramas of the interwar and post-war decades, “Blaxploitation” films of the post-Civil Rights era, and more recent arthouse contributions. In addition to regular film screenings, there will be a large amount of required course readings.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(236,2025,18,328,'1','Secondary Lit Pedagogy Mgt Theory','Jill Heinrich',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course equips students with content area reading methods, instructional strategies and management techniques at the secondary level.  Students complete a 40 hour practicum at the junior high or high school level, and they must provide their own transportation to the school site. It is highly recommended that this course must be taken PRIOR to student teaching. No alternative grade option.  This course requires an in-person practicum experience at the school. Students doing online learning are not eligible to take this course.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240','Writing Intensive'),
(237,2025,15,221,'4','Studio Art Topics: Illustration','Stevie Delgado',1,'ART',60,'ART 221 is an introduction to the fundamentals of character design, investigating different methods and approaches to creating compelling characters from initial concept sketches to fully realized designs. Students will explore the core principles of character design, including, silhouette, proportion, and expression, while learning how to infuse personality and emotion into their illustrations. Course activities will examine and determine influences of visual storytelling, paying attention to how shapes, color palettes, and clothing choices communicate traits and narratives. Students will develop a deeper understanding of how to approach character creation with intent and clarity through lectures, demonstrations, independent research, and critiques. No alternate grade option. This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $60 per student.','ART 103, ART 104, ART 200, ART 115','Fine Arts'),
(238,2025,25,781,'Adjunct Fall','Voice','Lynne Rothrock',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(239,2025,18,106,'2','Feminist Fairytales (W)','Katy Stavreva',1,'ENG',NULL,'Fairy tales have ignited the imagination of children and sophisticated salon readers, storytellers and political activists, authors and film-makers. Contemporary authors have used their familiar tropes and narratives to open up space for the mysterious and the emancipatory in stories of ordinary drudgery, neglect, abuse, injustice, violence. Case in point: the role of fairy-tales in the feminist fiction of American poet Anne Sexton, Irish-Canadian author Emma Donoghue, English writer Angela Carter, which will be the focus of our discussions and writing in this class. We will dedicate our work to developing a basic vocabulary and guided practice analyzing both literary adaptations of fairy-tales and scholarship about these adaptations. We will tone our academic writing muscles by writing in a variety of informal and formal formats, develop writing strategies, and reflect on writing as a multi-stage and recursive process. Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Humanities'),
(240,2025,25,353,'4','Civil War and Reconstruction','Phil Lucas',1,'HIS',NULL,'America at war with itself. The causes of the war and the attempt to rebuild the Union. No alternative grade option.','Junior Standing','Humanities'),
(241,2025,200,101,'Adjunct Spring','Experiential Learning','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Academic research experiences are opportunities for students to develop their understanding of professional methods and fields of study appropriate to a chosen discipline or proposed research question. The value of research for undergraduate students lies both in the intellectual development of the student and in the potential discovery of previously unknown information. Academic research experiences should therefore emphasize the development of disciplinary research skills and methodology; they should be substantial (in breadth, scope, maturity, and effort involved); and they should encourage students to engage with the planning, execution, and presentation of their research efforts.  In addition, sharing the results of one’s research is an important part of the research process, which calls upon the researcher to participate in a community of scholars. Research experiences therefore should be presented or published in some form.','','Experiential Learning'),
(242,2025,25,257,'7','Labor Economics','James Goodenberger',1,'ECB',NULL,'Exploration of a variety of current issues in labor markets from an economics perspective. Included among the questions to be addressed in this course are: Why do professional athletes, rock stars and movie stars earn so much more than the rest of us? What is the economic value of a college degree? Why do some college majors earn so much more than others? Who pays for and benefits from on-the-job training? Are workers better off when the government regulates safety in the workplace? How does discrimination in the labor market affect women, African Americans and other minorities? Why has union membership fallen so dramatically during the last 30 years? Who benefits from and who is hurt by increased international competition? Course activities will include a series of data collection/analysis/presentation projects. Alternate years.','ECB 101,ECB 102,STA 201,STA 348','Social Science'),
(243,2025,25,512,'Adjunct Spring','Reading and Conversation in Chemistry','Charley Liberko',0.25,'CHE',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),
(244,2025,25,731,'Adjunct Spring','French Horn: Brass Instruments','Peter Kortenkamp',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(245,2025,25,141,'7','Foundations: Cellular Biology','Sherri-Lynn Putz, Collin O\'Leary',1,'BIO',NULL,'The course introduces students to the principles of cell structure, cell function and information transfer by emphasizing the investigative approach to biological questions. Students design, execute, and interpret research. Research topics will vary with each instructor. This course is a prerequisite for most upper-level Biology courses.','','Science'),
(246,2025,25,782,'Adjunct Spring','Voice','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(247,2025,18,106,'6','Writing Rhetorically (W)','Jennifer Ferrell',1,'ENG',NULL,'At its most basic—but most profound—level, writing is about making choices, and this course teaches students how to understand other writers’ choices and how to make their own effective choices across a variety of writing situations. As such, this course is designed to ground students in the reading, writing, and rhetorical demands necessary for success in college and beyond. The study of rhetoric is foundational for this course because it allows students to both understand how other people’s texts affect readers and attempt persuasion and to compose effective and purposeful texts themselves. Rhetoric prepares students to participate in and respond to nearly any conceivable writing situation, whether it be another college course, certain professional demands, or personal needs. ADDITIONAL NOTE: This course will provide extra academic support and intensive preparation for the demands of writing at the college level. It is appropriate for students who have not done much academic writing in English in high school or who lack confidence in their writing. Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Humanities'),
(248,2025,25,348,'2','Mathematical Statistics II','Ann Cannon',1,'STA',NULL,'Typically the first term covers probability, random variables, sampling distributions and collecting data. The second term covers theory of estimation and hypothesis testing, linear and multiple regression, analysis of variance, and techniques for categorical data. Alternate years.','STA 347',NULL),
(249,2025,25,502,'Adjunct Fall','Capstone Preparation','Ann Cannon',0.25,'STA',NULL,'Students will be matched with an advisor from the Applied Statistics faculty and spend the semester working through the process of choosing a topic for their Senior Capstone Project in Statistics.  This will involve identifying a problem, finding appropriate data, and beginning an appropriate analysis.  Several topics may be explored before settling on the final topic, and the final topic must be approved by the advisor.  Common readings from the current literature in statistics may be assigned.  This adjunct course must be taken over Terms 1-4.  Students will meet with the instructor and/or advisor for approximately 2.5 hours per block.  Students will also work individually on the projects throughout the semester will meet with their advisor on the project.  The total time commitment will not exceed 10 hours per block.','',''),
(250,2025,50,718,'Adjunct Fall','Cornell Lyric Theatre','Benjamin Laur',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(251,2025,25,485,'7','Senior Capstone Project','Lauren Jepsen',1,'CSC',NULL,'Students will produce software or a research paper in stages with feedback from peers and instructors at each step. The experience will acquaint students with the software development and research processes that are widely used in the profession. The capstone project will serve as an example of students’ skills and creativity that employers and graduate schools look for in their candidates.','CSC 140, CSC 144, CSC 201, CSC 218, CSC 301, CSC 512',''),
(252,2025,20,101,'6','Beginning Latin I','Chris Hoklotubbe',1,'LAT',NULL,'Introduction to the language of ancient Rome, its empire, the middle ages, and the early modern world. Students will learn the essentials of grammar, vocabulary, and Roman history and culture through reading, speaking, and writing Latin; increase English vocabulary through Latin derivatives; and read selections from Latin writers from different eras. Offered two out of every three years.','','Language'),
(253,2025,25,260,'8','Modern Art','Michael Feinberg',1,'ART',NULL,'Investigation of the development of Modernism and its demise during the second half of the twentieth century. Multiple styles are discussed from the late nineteenth century to 1960. No alternative grade option. [AH]','','Humanities, Writing Encounter, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(254,2025,18,307,'8','Secondary Science Methods','Jill Heinrich',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course is designed to provide students with the opportunities to enhance science content knowledge and develop pedagogical skills needed for effective science teaching in middle and high school classrooms. A great deal of class time is devoted to experiential activities that deal with science content and process skills, and how to teach them to middle and high school students. Students will demonstrate their ability to effectively teach science using various strategies such as inquiry, modeling and computer simulations. This course is conducted at the practicum site. Transportation to and from the practicum site is the responsibility of the student. Course is graded Credit/No Credit.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240',NULL),
(255,2025,25,101,'2','Fundamentals of Music','Christopher Nakielski',1,'MUS',NULL,'An introductory music theory exploration, this course begins with pitch and rhythm reading skills; leads to understanding of intervals, scales, keys, and chords; and culminates in development of basic skills in musical analysis and composition. Previous experience in reading music is recommended, but not required. Preparation for MUS 110.','','Fine Arts'),
(256,2025,25,363,'4','Intro to Behavioral Neuroscience','Steven Neese',1,'PSY',NULL,'Neural and endocrine systems and their relationships with sensation, learning and memory, eating and drinking, sleep, sex, emotion, consciousness, communication, and psychological disorders. PSY 292 (Research Methods I) or PSY 394 strongly recommended.','PSY 161','Social Science'),
(257,2025,25,420,'6','Student Teaching II','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. ','EDU 410','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(258,2025,25,230,'5','Epidemiology','Ann Cannon',1,'STA',NULL,'An introduction to the methods used in the study of health and illness in human populations.  In particular, this course will include discussions on the role of epidemiology in public health both in the past and present, the different kinds of epidemiological studies and what conclusions can be made from them, and the process that epidemiologists use in infectious disease and outbreak investigations. The course will also introduce some of the statistical techniques required for epidemiological studies. Alternate years.','STA 201, STA 202',NULL),
(259,2025,24,201,'3','Statistical Methods I','Ann Cannon',1,'STA',NULL,'Elementary study of the science of data. Data collection, descriptive statistics, estimation, and hypothesis testing as applied to one- and two-variable problems.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(260,2025,18,106,'2','French Culture Through Lit and Film (W)','Rebecca Wines',1,'FRE',NULL,'Does wearing a beret and eating a baguette while walking a poodle near the Eiffel Tower make a person French? Is Frenchness defined by holding a particular passport? Is it about a cultural mindset? Is it demonstrated by cheering for a particular team during international sporting events? Through various fictional and non-fiction texts and films—as well as other media—this course will introduce you to selected topics in twentieth and twenty-first century French culture in order to stimulate your thinking about cultural context as well as intercultural learning and literacy. Together, we will read, write, reflect upon, and discuss what it has meant to be French over the last century or so, how these definitions have shifted over time, and what sorts of events and movements have shaped these ideas about identities and cultures.This course is taught in English; no prior knowledge of the French langauge or French and Francophone cultures is necessary.Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Humanities'),
(261,2025,150,700,'4','Vacation','Registrar Staff',0,'VAC',NULL,'Vacation blocks are open to seniors who are on track to complete 31 credits by block 8 of their senior year.  Non seniors must petition for permission to take fewer than 4 blocks per semester. If the student is on track to have 31 credits by the end of their senior year, the petition will be approved and the student will be registered for a vacation block. Otherwise, the student must explain in the petition how they will make up the missed credit. ','',''),
(262,2025,25,751,'Adjunct Spring','Scenery and Props HEIGHTS','Shawn Ketchum Johnson',0.25,'THE',NULL,'This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(263,2025,25,326,'1','Microbiology','Diane Gingerich Feil, Catherine Volle',1,'BIO',NULL,'Survey of microbial world with emphasis on bacterial genetics and metabolism, and the role of microbial activities in the environment. ','BIO 205','Science'),
(264,2025,15,292,'2','Research Methods I','Steven Neese',1,'PSY',NULL,'Introduction to research design with a focus on research ethics, sampling, measurement, reliability, internal and external validity, experimental design, introduction to quasi-experimental design, correlational design, observational research, and survey research.  Introduction to descriptive statistics (measures of central tendency, variability, confidence intervals of a single population mean), and univariate inferential statistics (independent samples t-test, dependent samples t-test, one-way ANOVA, one-way repeated measures ANOVA, confidence intervals of a difference score, estimates of effect size, Pearson’s coefficient of correlation, simple linear regression, chi squared).  Execution of all aspects of the research process including a literature search, hypothesis development, data collection, data analysis, and manuscript writing in APA style. No alternative grade option. Recommended in the sophomore year.','PSY 161','Social Science, Writing Intensive, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(265,2025,25,140,'4','Foundations of Computer Science','Lauren Jepsen',1,'CSC',NULL,'This course introduces students to problems that engage the interests of computer scientists and define the field. The course introduces students to object-oriented design, a principal discipline that computer scientists use to solve problems. Students learn to divide large problems into small problems, bundle related data with methods that operate on that data, and incorporate into new designs elements of previously completed designs. The course emphasizes creative expression using an abstract notation. Students practice designing, writing, testing, and presenting programs. Success in the course does not require previous programming experience.','','Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(266,2025,25,223,'7','Introduction to Data Science','Ann Cannon',1,'DSC',NULL,'Managing and interpreting an overwhelming amount of raw data is part of the foundation of our information society and economy. People use computers and statistics to translate, process, and visualize raw data, enabling new understandings that in turn contribute new knowledge to the world. Data Science is a newly developing field that merges ideas from both statistics and computer science to address these issues. In this course statistics will inform the discussion about what appropriate goals are for learning from the data and how the data will answer the questions raised. The computer science perspective will help us figure out which goals are actually feasible computationally, and how to achieve them. ','STA 201',''),
(267,2025,25,270,'5','Measurement/Evaluation Phys Act/Sports','Lewis Kanyiba',1,'KIN',NULL,'This course is an introduction to methods of measurement and evaluation in health, physical activity, and sports.  Various assessment tools and protocols in psychomotor, cognitive, and affective domains will be introduced.  Basic statistics, use of a computer for data organization and analysis, and adaptation of various tools and protocols for individuals with disabilities are presented.  Emphasis is placed on connecting theory and practice in assessing health-related physical fitness (aerobic capacity, musculoskeletal strength and endurance, flexibility, and body composition), psychomotor skills (agility, balance, coordination, power, speed, and reaction time), chosen sport-specific skills, and knowledge tests.  Clinical experiences will include data collection, statistical analysis, and use of obtained results to develop individual and program goals. Not open to first years.','','Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(268,2025,18,200,'1','Social Media and Social Justice (SYS)','Katie Sagal',1,'ENG',NULL,'Social media platforms like TikTok, X, Facebook, and more advertise themselves as tools for making and sustaining connections. For many, those connections function as a way of sharing information—about popular culture, life events, and social and political developments. In this course, we will discuss the potential that social media offers for inspiring genuine social change. Is Facebook doomed to be nothing more than a haven for conspiracy theories? Is X filled with nothing but bots? Do the geographic and demographic patterns of their users limit any meaningful impact? In this second-year seminar, we will combine critical readings and intense discussions with real-life projects like learning to write for social media in a professional capacity, writing and editing web copy, using modern media to create positive change in our communities, and generating community projects from conceptualization to completion.Only open to sophomores.','','Sophomore Year Seminar (SYS), Humanities'),
(269,2025,25,511,'Adjunct Fall','Intro Athletic Training Practicum (1/4)','Kristi Meyer',0.25,'KIN',NULL,'Provides an introductory supervised practical experience in the prevention, evaluation, treatment, management, and rehabilitation of athletic injuries and illnesses.Participation in learning Cornell Sports Medicine Assistant competency skills including taping, wrapping, stretching, and emergency care. This course may not be repeated for credit.','','CR'),
(270,2025,25,346,'6','Gender Diversity','Erin Davis',1,'SOC',NULL,'This course will focus on diverse gender identities, bodies, and social presentations. Social practices and pressures of gender will be examined in order to gain insight into the larger contemporary social meanings of gender. We will explore how individuals interpret and present their gender identities, the constraints on such interpretations and presentations, and the larger social implications of gender diversity and gender regulation on cultural ideals.This course may count toward the SOC and GSS majors. Alternate years.','SOC 101, GSS 171','Social Science, Writing Encounter'),
(271,2025,25,354,'6','Topics: U.S. Immigration Politcs/Policy','Laura Story Johnson',1,'POL',NULL,'This course will examine immigration law and policy in the current political landscape of the United States. Using a historical lens to contextualize how the political salience of immigration has shaped U.S. law and policy over time, we will analyze how demographic changes, public opinion, campaign tactics, and the media have shaped policy and policymaking when it comes to immigration. The course will explore legislation and policies aimed at immigrants, including the circumstances under which immigrants are permitted to enter the United States and the circumstances under which they can be forced to leave. While comparisons to the immigration law and policy of other countries may be referenced, this course focuses primarily on immigration law and policy in the United States.','POL 172, POL 254, POL 256','Social Science'),
(272,2025,18,381,'4','Topics: Professional Writing','Scott Morris',1,'ENG',NULL,'This course will explore the communication needs and processes of writers in professional settings. We will discuss the ways professional documents are made and used, with real-world experience as our class works with a real-world client to produce documentation. To accomplish those large-issue objectives, this class also seeks to shape individual writing skills through a rhetorical approach to grammar instruction, understanding the parts of speech, but also the choices writers have at the sentence level, and the effects those choices have on the document’s users.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, ENG 201, ENG 215, ENG 225','Writing Intensive'),
(273,2025,22,327,'7','Organic Chemistry Laboratory','Charley Liberko, Andrea Dunn, Harmeet Bhoday',1,'CHE',NULL,'Practical laboratory aspects of organic chemistry. Isolation and purification of substances; one-step transformations of substances; and, possibly, synthesis projects.','CHE 326','Science, Writing Encounter'),
(274,2025,25,202,'5','Analytical Chemistry','Andrea Dunn, Cindy Strong, John Baur',1,'CHE',NULL,'Concepts of analysis, volumetric techniques, and an introduction to instrumental techniques. ','CHE 122, CHE 161','Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(275,2025,25,715,'Adjunct Fall','The Rehearsal Process CHILD','Caroline Price',0.25,'THE',NULL,'Participation in rehearsal process as a performer or on production team for a minimum of six weeks.','',''),
(276,2025,25,430,'8','Exercise Testing & Prescription','Justus Hallam',1,'KIN',NULL,'Practical application of physiological principles related to the assessment of functional physical capacity and the prescription of exercise for healthy adult populations, based upon American College of Sports Medicine (ACSM) health-related fitness recommendations. Development of practical skills and professionalism for performing fitness assessments, including: the pre-participation screening; heart rate and blood pressure at rest and during exercise; and assessments of body composition, cardiorespiratory fitness, muscular strength, and flexibility. Includes interpretation of health-related fitness assessment results and the prescription of appropriate fitness programs for improving musculoskeletal strength and flexibility, cardiorespiratory fitness, and weight loss. ','KIN 207, BIO 207, KIN 208, KIN 315, KIN 328, KIN 329',''),
(277,2025,25,126,'4','Topics: Magic and the Occult','Steven Sacks',1,'REL',NULL,'An introduction to the place of magic in Western Civilization and beyond, with a focus on its understanding of the natural world, philosophy, theology and the role of human beings in the cosmos.','','Humanities'),
(278,2025,25,762,'Adjunct Spring','Piano','Jessica Monnier',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(279,2025,25,325,'1','Renaissance Worlds on Page and Stage','Katy Stavreva',1,'ENG',NULL,'Step into the literary culture of the English Renaissance, when Europeans’ view of the self and the world was profoundly altered by encounters, exchanges, and violent clashes with people of unfamiliar religious, racial, ethnic backgrounds. Study the poetic and dramatic works of the irreverent Christopher Marlowe, venerated knight and sonneteer Philip Sidney, the first English professional woman poet Aemilia Lanyer, city wits Thomas Middleton and Thomas Dekker, etc., and explore how they brought to life distant and closet landscapes and cultures, and how they used them as metaphors for intellectual, civic, religious, and erotic inquiry. Breach the divide of the centuries to place these surprisingly relevant old texts in dialogue with the burning issues of our times. Practice analyzing dramatic dialogue and poetic expression, collaborate in historical research and creative experiment, play with book craft and develop letterpress printing skills, and develop the editing skills to help newcomers to these texts navigate their enticing contents. The class can function as a Research Seminar fulfilling the capstone requirement for the Literature and Society, and the Multimedia and Digital Writing concentrations of the English major. It also counts as elective for the GSS major. Alternate years.','ENG 111, WRT 100, WRT 016, ENG 201, ENG 202, ENG 215, ENG 225','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(280,2025,50,0,'Adjunct Spring','Pending Individual Project','Registrar Staff',1,'PROJ',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, individual project. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the individual project block.','',''),
(281,2025,25,315,'3','Programming Language Concepts','Leon Tabak',1,'CSC',NULL,'Principles of design and implementation of high-level programming languages. Language definition structure, run-time behavior. Alternative programming paradigms, including functional languages. Programming examples from selected languages. Alternate years.','CSC 144',''),
(282,2025,25,161,'5','Fundamentals of Psychological Science','Katelyn Pitcher',1,'PSY',NULL,'Scientific study of behavior. Topics may include learning, development, personality, perception, physiological bases of behavior, the behavior of individuals in groups, and abnormal behavior.','','Social Science'),
(283,2025,25,243,'5','Investments','Huan Cai',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course provides a comprehensive overview of investments from the capital market investor\'s perspective.  The primary objective of this course is to introduce the modern portfolio theory and its applications in investment analysis.  The focus of the course is on basic principles that represent important long-term knowledge. Institutional details and current, potentially short-living trends are not the focus. ','ECB 101, ECB 102, ECB 151, STA 201, STA 348','Social Science'),
(284,2025,25,754,'Adjunct Fall','Theatre Administration SISTERS','Scott Olinger',0.25,'THE',NULL,'This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(285,2025,25,235,'2','Field Biology','Isaac Winkler, Josh Otten',1,'BIO',NULL,'Field biology will help students gain an appreciation for the world around them while developing employable biological skills. We will visit local ecosystems such as prairies, woodlands, ponds, and streams during six field trips. Students will gain knowledge and hands-on experience in basic field skills necessary for various ecological and environmental careers or studies. After each field trip, the exploration will continue under the microscope and in the lab, including data analysis with commonly used ecological software.','BIO 142','Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(286,2025,25,142,'5','International Politics','Laura Story Johnson',1,'POL',NULL,'How and why states compete and cooperate internationally. Addresses concepts such as the balance of power between states, collective security through treaties and international organizations, nuclear deterrence, and the growing influence of non-Western states. Typically includes historical and current case studies. ','','Social Science, International Relations & Comparative Government, Writing Encounter'),
(287,2025,25,274,'1','Social Psychology','Samantha Heiman',1,'PSY',NULL,'An examination of the thoughts, feelings, and behaviors of individuals within their social environment. Topics will include: conformity, propaganda, persuasion, social cognition, self-justification, human aggression, prejudice, attraction, and loving relationships. Emphasis will be placed on critically examining experimentally-derived theories and testing them within naturalistic settings. This will involve data collection off-campus on a weekend.','','Social Science'),
(288,2025,25,782,'Adjunct Spring','Voice','Lynne Rothrock',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(289,2025,25,346,'5','Fluid Mechanics','Niloofar Kamran',1,'EGR',NULL,'An introduction to the mechanics of liquids and gases. Topics include classifications of flows, fluid statics, Lagrangian and Eulerian descriptions of fluids, Bernoulli and energy equations, closed system and control volume concepts, dimensional analysis and similarity. Applications of fluids to engineering including internal flow, flow in pipes and ducts, external flow, lift and drag forces. This course includes a visit to IIHR – Hydroscience & Engineering at University of Iowa. No Alternate Grade option.','EGR 235, MAT 122',''),
(290,2025,25,315,'7','Physiology of Exercise','Justus Hallam',1,'KIN',NULL,'In-depth study of the human responses to exercise and exercise training, including: substrate metabolism and energy production during exercise, cardiorespiratory and neuromuscular function during acute exercise, cardiovascular and neuromuscular adaptations to exercise training, endocrine responses to physical activity, and thermoregulation. Introduction to current scientific methodologies and the development of practical skills through experiential laboratory activities.','KIN 207, BIO 207, KIN 208, BIO 208','Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(291,2025,25,771,'Adjunct Fall','Viola: String Instruments','Michelle Bennett',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(292,2025,15,211,'7','Sculpture','Stevie Delgado',1,'ART',75,'The making of three-dimensional art forms using a variety of materials and techniques. May include both analogue and/or digital processes depending on instructor. This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $75 per student. No alternative grade option. [SA]','ART 103, ART 104, ART 200, ART 115, ART 221','Fine Arts'),
(293,2025,20,200,'1','Holocaust: Trauma and Memory (SYS)','Steven Sacks',1,'REL',NULL,'Genocide is an experience, memory and reaction characterized by Trauma. This course explores Trauma as a framework for understanding the origins and impact of the horrors of Genocide, and of pursuing healing. Utilizing the Holocaust of the Jewish people in the Twentieth Century as a case study, we will explore the cultural, ethical, psychological and political origins and interpretations of this event from historical studies to current events, including its current role for the state of Israel. This course will seek, therefore, to assess the impact of Genocide not only on those who experienced it, but also the way that it impacts and influences political, ethical and social debates in our culture and society. Only open to sophmores.','','Sophomore Year Seminar (SYS),Humanities'),
(294,2025,5,510,'Adjunct Fall','Introduction to Book Arts','Katy Stavreva',0.25,'ENG',NULL,'The course will introduce participants to the field of book arts, including page design, typesetting, letterpress and monograph printing, as well as traditional and experimental bookbinding techniques through demonstrations and hands-on experience. Sessions may also include field trips to libraries and museums, or fine presses. To earn credit, students must complete all projects. The schedule of workshops and fieldtrips will be finalized at an informational session to be held on the first Friday afternoon of the semester to accommodate participants’ responsibilities.','Katy Stavreva','Fine Arts, CR'),
(295,2025,23,207,'5','Human Systems Physiology & Anatomy I','Kristi Meyer',1,'BIO',NULL,'Part I in a two part series of a fundamental study of the complementarity of human anatomical structure and physiological function of the integumentary, endocrine, nervous, muscular, cardiovascular, respiratory, digestive, and renal systems.  Special emphasis on development of mechanistic understanding of organ system function and integrated physiological function across systems to promote homeostatic regulation in the human body. Inclusion of experiential learning through laboratory activities. Previously listed as KIN 207.','','Science'),
(296,2025,12,246,'6','Global Health in India FEE1','Aparna Thomas',1,'POL',NULL,'This course will critically investigate the complex ways in which gender relationships shape history, ideology, economy, and polity in developing countries. The role and status of Asian women will be examined to enable students to compare and contrast non-Western experiences with Western experiences. The forces of modernity and the impact on colonialism will also be discussed especially in relation to the economic and political conditions of the non-Western world and development. Alternate years. This course also counts towards the GSS major.Location: IndiaTotal course cost: $4,350. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog.This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','','Social Science, International Relations & Comparative Government'),
(297,2025,25,121,'3','Calculus of a Single Variable','Jim Freeman',1,'MAT',NULL,'Differential and integral calculus of functions of one real variable and analytic geometry of two variables.','three and one-half years of high school mathematics, including trigonometry, or permission of instructor. An ACT Math score of 25 or above, or SAT Math score of 570 or above is recommended.This course is not open to students who have completed MAT 120.','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(298,2025,18,225,'6','Introduction to Multimedia Writing','Katie Sagal',1,'ENG',NULL,'This course is an introduction to professional and media writing, as well as to the English major. Students will engage with a wide variety of media, such as digital publishing, podcasts, storytelling in video games, social media campaigns, and writing for marketing. Students will gain familiarity with the current best practices in writing for media, including rhetorical strategies, visual design, and stylistic conventions. With a particular focus on contemporary forms of writing, this course will introduce students to professions related to writing and communication. Media-specific projects vary depending upon the professor’s expertise. Sagal: Focus on writing for marketing contexts.  Morris: Focus on creative multimedia projects and professional writing for the arts.Required for English Major concentrators in Multimedia and Digital Writing.Prerequisite: FYW course','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100','Humanities, Writing Intensive'),
(299,2025,25,410,'1','Student Teaching I','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements.','All 200- and 300-level Education courses, approval of the Education Department','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(300,2025,25,276,'4','Multicultural Psychology','Katelyn Pitcher',1,'PSY',NULL,'An examination and critique of psychological knowledge from a multicultural perspective. This course focuses on understanding individual and cultural identity and worldviews, the intersectionality of these aspects of identity, and how understanding culture helps us understand each other and ourselves. Other topics include: cultural variations in concepts of personality, intelligence, human development, social behavior, gender, and abnormal behavior; research methodology issues; culture and communication; and the cultural foundations of Western psychology. This course emphasizes cultural and psychological perspectives on oppression, prejudice, violence, and racism using current examples of American and international incidents. This course is designed to help students better understand themselves and members of diverse communities with whom our students will likely encounter during their education, careers, and life overall.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive, Writing Encounter'),
(301,2025,99,711,'Adjunct Spring','Chamber Ensembles Woodwinds','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(302,2025,25,110,'2','Great Mathematical Ideas','Jim Freeman',1,'MAT',NULL,'Investigation of a variety of great mathematical discoveries past and present. The ideas investigated will not require significant previous mathematical background, but will require the student to actively participate in the process of mathematical discovery. Only by doing mathematics can the creativity, beauty, and mathematical importance of these great ideas be understood. Specific content varies with the course instructor, but may include subjects such as knot theory, origami, game theory, the nature of infinity, or chaos and fractals. Recommended for non-mathematics majors. This course is not open to students who have completed MAT 120 or higher. This course does not count toward a mathematics major or minor.','Two years of high school algebra','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(303,2025,25,120,'4','Calculus-Single Variable Part II','Fabian Candelaria',1,'MAT',NULL,'Differential and integral calculus of functions of one real variable and analytic geometry of two variables. This course emphasizes review of precalculus material and is appropriate for students who feel they need more time in order to succeed in calculus. Unless a departmental exception is granted, this course combination of MAT 119 and MAT 120 must be taken in consecutive terms. This course is not open to students who have completed MAT 121 or higher.','MAT 119','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(304,2025,25,102,'3','Microeconomics','James Goodenberger',1,'ECB',NULL,'Basic microeconomic analysis of consumer choice, the business firm, and resource markets in labor, capital, and land. Analysis and critique of government policy in problem areas such as monopoly power and government regulations and expenditures.','two years of algebra in high school','Social Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(305,2025,50,0,'3','Pending Internship','Registrar Staff',1,'INTRN',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, internship. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the internship block.','',''),
(306,2025,25,260,'3','Individual/Family Life Educ & Wellness','Frannie Malone',1,'KIN',NULL,'This course will examine health from a broad perspective including aspects of social, emotional, spiritual, and mental health.  Special topics will include substance abuse and the impact of psycho-social factors on personal wellness, family life, and community well-being.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Encounter, Writing Encounter'),
(307,2025,25,326,'3','Organic Chemistry II Lecture','Harmeet Bhoday',1,'CHE',NULL,'Continuation of CHE 225. Methods of synthesis and the reactions of organic compounds.','CHE 225','Science'),
(308,2025,18,106,'5','Morals of our Stories (FYW)','Genevieve Migely',1,'PHI',NULL,'This course will examine ethical theories and notions embedded in the discourse of storytelling. Moral lessons and norms are conveyed in the pages as the tale unfolds and the characters develop. Through the use of fable, fiction and film, the ethical principles of major philosophical systems, such as relativism, utilitarianism, egoism, deontological and virtue ethics, will be discerned, analyzed, and critically evaluated. This moral foundation will set the stage for the exploration of how such viewpoints are captured in various stories, and what the tales have to tell us about ourselves, our human condition, and our obligations to each other morally, socially and politically. As a seminar in first-year writing, strong emphasis will be placed on the development of academic writing skills through formal and informal writing assignments, guided writing and revision processes, and an exploration of writing techniques and strategies to hone reflective and effective writing skills. Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW)'),
(309,2025,20,205,'5','Introduction-Latin Literature & Culture','John Gruber-Miller',1,'LAT',NULL,'Intensive engagement with a cultural topic through reading Latin texts of the Republic or Empire, in tandem with listening, speaking, or writing in the target language. Topics may include Roman comedy, Roman performance culture, Roman banquets, or Roman elections. Offered two out of every three years.','LAT 103','Language, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(310,2025,25,122,'5','Calculus of Several Variables','Fabian Candelaria',1,'MAT',NULL,'Continuation of Calculus of a Single Variable, including further techniques of integration, vectors, and differential and integral calculus of several variables. ','MAT 120, MAT 121','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(311,2025,5,485,'6','Problems','Collin O\'Leary',1,'BMB',NULL,'Investigation of a biological problem, including a review of the literature, collection and interpretation of data, and writing of a research report. May be repeated once for credit. Intended for seniors or advanced juniors, this is a capstone experience for Biology and BMB majors. Arrangements must be made with the instructor before registering. May be repeated once for credit. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation for Ingenuity in Action. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Writing Encounter'),
(312,2025,18,302,'8','Secondary English Methods','Jill Heinrich',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course is designed to introduce students to the methods and strategies of teaching English at the secondary level.  Students will focus on several topics and themes that are of great importance to practicing and aspiring teachers. These topics include recent debates about the teaching of English, active learning opportunities with literature, methods of instruction, curriculum development and alignment with standards, the use of technology in teaching and in student research, and assignment design and evaluation. This course is conducted at the practicum site. Transportation to and from the practicum site is the responsibility of the student. Course is graded Credit/No Credit. This course requires an in-person practicum experience at the school. Students doing online learning are not eligible to take this course.','EDU 301, EDU 328','Credit/No Credit'),
(313,2025,25,731,'Adjunct Fall','Trombone: Brass Instruments','Drew Bonner',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(314,2025,25,141,'3','Foundations: Cellular Biology','Sherri-Lynn Putz, Nicole Green',1,'BIO',NULL,'The course introduces students to the principles of cell structure, cell function and information transfer by emphasizing the investigative approach to biological questions. Students design, execute, and interpret research. Research topics will vary with each instructor. This course is a prerequisite for most upper-level Biology courses.','','Science'),
(315,2025,25,111,'6','Foundations of Kinesiology','Frannie Malone',1,'KIN',NULL,'Historical and philosophical foundation of physical education. Current issues in research and literature. Biological, physiological, and sociological aspects of sport and exercise.','',''),
(316,2025,99,713,'Adjunct Spring','Jazz Ensemble','Benjamin Laur',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(317,2025,24,201,'2','Statistical Methods I','Fabian Candelaria',1,'STA',NULL,'Elementary study of the science of data. Data collection, descriptive statistics, estimation, and hypothesis testing as applied to one- and two-variable problems.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(318,2025,18,755,'Adjunct Fall','Dance Performance','Amy Simonson',0.25,'THE',NULL,'Dance Performance is a course open to students with various dance backgrounds and levels who seek to enhance their technical and performance skills beyond the block format.  Class will focus around warm-up, diagonal exercises, and movement compositions.  Techniques to be explored in this course include, contemporary modern, jazz, and classical ballet. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Ingenuity in Action, Creative Expression'),
(319,2025,150,700,'5','Vacation','Registrar Staff',0,'VAC',NULL,'Vacation blocks are open to seniors who are on track to complete 31 credits by block 8 of their senior year.  Non seniors must petition for permission to take fewer than 4 blocks per semester. If the student is on track to have 31 credits by the end of their senior year, the petition will be approved and the student will be registered for a vacation block. Otherwise, the student must explain in the petition how they will make up the missed credit.','',''),
(320,2025,25,732,'Adjunct Fall','Trumpet: Brass Instruments','Desmond Cervantez',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(321,2025,99,702,'Adjunct Spring','Composition','Drew Bonner',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'Original composition for various media, beginning with smaller forms. May be repeated for credit. This course may be taken for 0.25, 0.5 or 1.0 credits.  No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(322,2025,18,103,'5','Drawing I','Stevie Delgado',1,'ART',100,'This course explores traditional and contemporary approaches to the technical, analytical and theoretical skills related to drawing. Students will work with a variety of materials and methods to develop a thorough understanding of line, value, volume, mark-making, composition, and image construction. While perceptual and observational drawing is a major component of the class, we will approach drawing as a tool for exploring visual languages, a tool to experiment with ideas visually and a tool of self-improvement. Working with still life, landscape, human figures and abstraction, students will learn a wide variety of practical drawing skills and also bolster their visual literacy and critical reasoning skills. Course format consists primarily of studio work. The course instructor provides guidance through lecture, demonstration, individual feedback and critique. Grading is based on willingness to experiment and take chances, time invested in the work, participation in class critiques, improvement throughout the block and implementation of concepts covered in class (regardless of student’s skill level). The course work will require some written work.  No alternative grade option. This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $100 per student. [SA]','','Fine Arts'),
(323,2025,25,245,'1','Global Health','David Yamanishi',1,'POL',NULL,'The course will introduce students to key global health issues. Students will gain an understanding of contemporary global health problems, their determinants, distribution, and prevention/response strategies. Particular attention will be paid to the links between global health and social and economic development. This course focuses on developing countries and on the health of the poor.','','International Relations & Comparative Politics, Social Science'),
(324,2025,25,110,'7','Great Mathematical Ideas','Melanie King',1,'MAT',NULL,'Investigation of a variety of great mathematical discoveries past and present. The ideas investigated will not require significant previous mathematical background, but will require the student to actively participate in the process of mathematical discovery. Only by doing mathematics can the creativity, beauty, and mathematical importance of these great ideas be understood. Specific content varies with the course instructor, but may include subjects such as knot theory, origami, game theory, the nature of infinity, or chaos and fractals. Recommended for non-mathematics majors. This course is not open to students who have completed MAT 120 or higher. This course does not count toward a mathematics major or minor. Prerequisite: Two years of high school algebra.','','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(325,2025,10,306,'5','Current Events in French-Speaking World','Devan Baty',1,'FRE',NULL,'The content of this course focuses on current events in the French-speaking world, allowing students to develop advanced composition and conversation skills while refining their grammar in writing and speaking. Building vocabulary and comprehending complex grammatical structures are emphasized through discussion and analysis of current events in the media. Students interact virtually with native speakers from the French-speaking world. Offered once every three years.','FRE 205, FRE 206','Writing Encounter'),
(326,2025,18,106,'5','Hazardous Journeys, Grand Adventures (W)','Katie Sagal',1,'ENG',NULL,'What does it mean to be a traveler? An explorer? An immigrant? How do we reconcile our sense of self in each new context we uncover, on every new ground we tread? How does movement through space and culture fundamentally change us? Humans have been thinking about what it means to exist, to survive, and, even, to thrive or wither in strange lands for centuries. Indeed, because it is inevitably tied up with histories of colonialism, empire, race, gender, and able-bodiedness, travel is no simple thing. In this first-year writing seminar, we will explore the complexities of identity negotiation and formation through a selection of global travel literatures, loosely conceived. The course will encompass a variety of challenging readings and viewings that we will process through extensive in-class discussions, brief oral presentations, small group work, and evidence-based writing assignments. Ultimately, the course is also designed to inspire reflection and critical thinking about our own context and self-identity.ADDITIONAL NOTE: This course will provide extra academic support and intensive preparation for the demands of writing at the college level. It is appropriate for students who have not done much academic writing in English in high school or who lack confidence in their writing.Not open to students who have previously completed a First Year Writing course.ADDITIONAL NOTE: This course will provide extra academic support and intensive preparation for the demands of writing at the college level. It is appropriate for students who have not done much academic writing in English in high school or who lack confidence in their writing.Not open to students who have previously completed a First Year Writing course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Humanities'),
(327,2025,25,320,'2','Hydrogeology','Rhawn Denniston',1,'GEO',NULL,'The study of the chemistry and movement of groundwater and surface water and their interactions with earth surface processes. Includes field- and laboratory-based projects, fieldtrips, and reading of primary literature. Same course as ENV 301. Alternate years. ','GEO 101, GEO 105, GEO 111, GEO 122, GEO 123, GEO 130, GEO 160, GEO 161, GEO 105, GEO 122, GEO 160, ENV 201, ENV 202','Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter, Writing Encounter'),
(328,2025,16,334,'7','Biochemistry','Catherine Volle',1,'CHE',NULL,'Cellular metabolism, with emphasis on energy extraction pathways and energy homeostasis. The approach is primarily mechanistic with a quantitative discussion of kinetics, free-energy changes, and the electrochemistry of electron transport chains.','BIO 205, CHE 327','Science'),
(329,2025,25,237,'8','Care and Prevention of Athletic Injuries','Courtney Zierten',1,'KIN',35,'Prevention and treatment of athletic injuries, taping experience, understanding the principles of athletic training, and first aid and emergency care.This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $35 per student for CPR certification. Required of all students, even those who have been previously certified.','',''),
(330,2025,18,225,'5','Introduction to Multimedia Writing','Scott Morris',1,'ENG',NULL,'This course is an introduction to professional and media writing, as well as to the English major. Students will engage with a wide variety of media, such as digital publishing, podcasts, storytelling in video games, social media campaigns, and writing for marketing. Students will gain familiarity with the current best practices in writing for media, including rhetorical strategies, visual design, and stylistic conventions. With a particular focus on contemporary forms of writing, this course will introduce students to professions related to writing and communication. Media-specific projects vary depending upon the professor’s expertise. Sagal: Focus on writing for marketing contexts.  Morris: Focus on creative multimedia projects and professional writing for the arts.Required for English Major concentrators in Multimedia and Digital Writing.','ENG 111, WRT 016, WRT 100','Humanities, Writing Intensive'),
(331,2025,25,782,'Adjunct Fall','Voice','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(332,2025,25,161,'7','Fundamentals of Psychological Science','Kris Robbins',1,'PSY',NULL,'Scientific study of behavior. Topics may include learning, development, personality, perception, physiological bases of behavior, the behavior of individuals in groups, and abnormal behavior.','','Social Science'),
(333,2025,25,704,'Adjunct Fall','Instrumental Techniques Percussion','Virginia Armstrong',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'Development of basic performing techniques. Study and evaluation of procedures and materials for elementary and intermediate instrumental teaching. No alternate grade option.','',''),
(334,2025,25,212,'7','Sports and American Society','Rebecca Wines',1,'KIN',NULL,'Exploration of the impact of amateur and professional sports on the American way of life. Sample topics include women in sports, sports and the African-American community, sports as big business, and the relationship between sport and education. Readings reflecting a variety of viewpoints about the role of sports in American society will be selected from contemporary literature.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive, Writing Encounter'),
(335,2025,18,106,'3','Climate Change (W)','Rhawn Denniston',1,'GEO',NULL,'An examination of changes in Earth\'s climate with particular focus on the last 20,000 years. Topics include greenhouse and icehouse worlds, climate reconstruction techniques, and factors driving climate change. Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Science'),
(336,2025,15,412,'6','Senior Project in Creative Writing','Rebecca Entel',1,'ENG',NULL,'This course serves as the second half of the capstone experience for students completing the English major\'s Creative Writing concentration. Students will work independently on a creative writing project started in previous workshops, meet individually with the instructor to discuss their progress and work on successive drafts, and meet with other students for an intensive workshop of projects. Students will also work with the instructor to create, complete, and discuss a reading list relevant to their project. The goal is to produce work for publication and/or public performance. The Senior Project Workshop will be conducted as a combination of workshop with other course members, independent study, and one-on-one mentoring. The block will also include professional training in the submission and publication process as well as advice about graduate school and careers in writing.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation for Ingenuity in Action. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','ENG 411, ENG 305','Fine Arts, Writing Intensive'),
(337,2025,25,420,'5','Student Teaching II','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','EDU 410','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(338,2025,15,108,'5','Costume Construction','Jenny Kelchen',1,'THE',75,'Introduction to costume construction technology, including sewing, pattern reading and draping, through classroom and laboratory work. A brief survey of dress throughout history and introductory costume design project are included. Students are required to help in the construction of costumes for an upcoming Theatre Department production. This course has a materials fee of approximately $75 per student.','','Fine Arts'),
(339,2025,25,240,'6','Education and Culture','Sarah Doyle',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course examines American core culture and the essential role that public education plays in that culture.  Specifically, it explores the socio-civic mandate which requires schools to prepare students for participation in a democratic society; in doing so, students are encouraged to understand and be sensitive to the values, beliefs, lifestyles and attitudes of individuals and diverse groups found in a pluralistic society.  Not open to juniors and seniors without instructor permission. No alternate grade option.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(340,2025,25,210,'1','Corporate Finance','Huan Cai',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course provides a basic understanding of business finance from the company\'s perspective.  The primary objective of this course is to introduce basic financial concepts and decision-making techniques, and applications in financing and investment decisions in a corporation.  Focus on two major areas of corporate finance: corporate investing (capital budgeting) and financing (capital structure) activities.','ECB 101, ECB 102, ECB 151','Social Science'),
(341,2025,25,343,'7','Music Theory IV','James Martin',1,'MUS',NULL,'Continuation of MUS 310, with emphasis on aural skills, structural analysis, and formal designs of music from the common-practice period. No alternate grade option. Offered in alternate years.','MUS 310',NULL),
(342,2025,25,215,'6','Educational Psychology','Madison Parker',1,'EDU',NULL,'The factors that influence the nature and quality of growth, development, and learning during the educational process. Examination, through the use of recent research and illustrative examples, of important psychological characteristics of children and adolescents as learners, and of teachers and the teaching process in the elementary and secondary schools. Fifteen practicum hours required in the schools. Personal transportation will be needed for two separate days in this course. Not open to juniors and seniors without permission of instructor. No alternative grade option.','','Social Science'),
(343,2025,18,281,'4','Jazz Studio I','Amy Simonson',1,'THE',NULL,'Jazz is a movement based course designed to provide intermediate level students with continuing skill and technical developmental training in jazz dance. Class will focus on warm-up, diagonal exercises, and center combinations to improve alignment and increase technical efficiency in jazz.','','Fine Arts'),
(344,2025,99,701,'Adjunct Spring','Music Performance Seminar','Jama Stilwell',0,'MUS',NULL,'A semester-long program requiring attendance at a number of musical events. The number of required events changes from semester to semester. Students should contact the Department of Music each semester for details.','',''),
(345,2025,24,122,'8','Chemical Principles II','Catherine Volle, Collin O\'Leary',1,'CHE',NULL,'Rates of chemical reactions, equilibrium, acids and bases, electrochemistry, and an introduction to thermodynamics. Reactions and properties of selected elements and their compounds.','CHE 121','Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(346,2025,25,715,'Adjunct Spring','The Rehearsal Process MOCK','Scott Olinger',0.25,'THE',NULL,'Participation in rehearsal process as a performer or on production team for a minimum of six weeks.','',''),
(347,2025,25,221,'2','Linear Algebra','Melanie King',1,'MAT',NULL,'Existence and uniqueness of solutions to linear systems. Linear transformations, linear independence, spanning vectors, vector spaces, basis and dimension, orthogonality, eigenvalues and eigenvectors. Students will be required to prepare written and oral presentations on a linear algebra application approved by the instructor.','MAT 120, MAT 121, CSC 151, MAT 122',NULL),
(348,2025,25,410,'4','Student Teaching I','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','All 200- and 300-level Education courses, approval of the Education Department','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(349,2025,25,101,'8','Macroeconomics','A\'amer Farooqi',1,'ECB',NULL,'Basic macroeconomic theory. Analytical evaluation of the determinants of national output, inflation, and unemployment. Examination of fiscal and monetary policies and issues in international trade and payments. Introduction of tools necessary to analyze economic models.','','Social Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(350,2025,25,772,'Adjunct Fall','Cello: String Instruments','James Ellis',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(351,2025,20,103,'5','Beginning Spanish III','Michael Mosier',1,'SPA',NULL,'Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development.','SPA 102, SPA 102C','Language'),
(352,2025,15,306,'3','Sound Design','Shawn Ketchum Johnson',1,'THE',NULL,'null','',''),
(353,2025,25,315,'4','Physiology of Exercise','Justus Hallam',1,'KIN',NULL,'In-depth study of the human responses to exercise and exercise training, including: substrate metabolism and energy production during exercise, cardiorespiratory and neuromuscular function during acute exercise, cardiovascular and neuromuscular adaptations to exercise training, endocrine responses to physical activity, and thermoregulation. Introduction to current scientific methodologies and the development of practical skills through experiential laboratory activities.','KIN 207, BIO 207, KIN 208','Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(354,2025,25,725,'Adjunct Spring','Pop/Contemporary Ensemble','Benjamin Laur',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'CCM (contemporary commercial music) performance ensemble. Students will learn songs together from the popular repertoire, including folk/country, rock, pop, and R&B, and rehearse and perform in groups. Some facility with voice or an instrument (keyboard, guitar, bass guitar, drums/percussion suggested) required. Placement by audition. Repeatable for credit.','',''),
(355,2025,18,330,'5','Intermediate Methods Reading/Lang Arts','Madison Parker',1,'INT',NULL,'This course provides in-depth exploration and practice in teaching reading and language arts at the intermediate level, grounded in the science of reading.  Building upon foundational knowledge, students will develop advanced strategies for fostering literacy development in diverse classrooms.  There is particular emphasis upon evidence-based practices derived from the science of reading, focusing on comprehension instruction, vocabulary development, writing integration and the use of assessment.  Through a combination of theoretical study, hands-on activities and classroom simulations, students will gain the skills necessary to design and implement effective reading and language arts instruction to meet the needs of all learners.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240',NULL),
(356,2025,20,101,'6','Beginning Spanish I','Juana New Gavidia',1,'SPA',NULL,'Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development.','','Language'),
(357,2025,25,202,'3','Ethics','Genevieve Migely',1,'PHI',NULL,'This course engages students in the nature and dynamics of ethical reasoning and discourse to foster a set of skills that enables us to think critically and openly about our own and others’ moral values and frameworks. Course considers applications to contemporary moral questions such as sex, gender and race relations, environmental sustainability, human and animal rights and liberties. Readings from ancient, modern, and contemporary moral philosophers.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(358,2025,25,142,'4','Foundations: Organismal Biology','Rebecca Richtsmeier-Ross, Josh Otten',1,'BIO',NULL,'The topics of genetics, evolution, speciation, classification, the diversity of life, ecology, biological communities, and animal behavior. This course is a prerequisite for all upper-level Biology courses.','','Science'),
(359,2025,25,120,'6','Calculus-Single Variable Part II','Melanie King',1,'MAT',NULL,'Differential and integral calculus of functions of one real variable and analytic geometry of two variables. This course emphasizes review of precalculus material and is appropriate for students who feel they need more time in order to succeed in calculus. Unless a departmental exception is granted, this course combination of MAT 119 and MAT 120 must be taken in consecutive terms. This course is not open to students who have completed MAT 121 or higher.','MAT 119','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(360,2025,50,0,'Adjunct Spring','Pending Individual Project','Registrar Staff',1,'PROJ',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, individual project. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the individual project block.','',''),
(361,2025,18,285,'6','Experimental Engineering','Mazhar Iqbal',1,'EGR',NULL,'Principles and procedures that working engineers use to guarantee the quality of designs and products. Topics include calibration, sampling, curve fitting, hypothesis testing, measurement uncertainty, and probability distributions. Emphasis is placed on conducting experiements and reporting and presenting results to both technical and non-technical audiences','EGR 231, EGR 271','Writing Encounter'),
(362,2025,50,0,'6','Pending Individual Project','Registrar Staff',1,'PROJ',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, individual project. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the individual project block.','',''),
(363,2025,25,315,'1','Genetics','Sherri-Lynn Putz, Sophie Gillett',1,'BIO',NULL,'Principles of inheritance in plants and animals. Emphasis on the laws of heredity and molecular genetics. Laboratory research in molecular genetics. Not to be taken in the same academic year as BIO 205. Juniors and seniors only.','BIO 205','Science'),
(364,2025,15,324,'2','Elementary Physical Education Mthds','Lewis Kanyiba',1,'KIN',NULL,'Methods for movement education and preparation for the teaching of rhythmic activities, low and high organization games, and elementary gymnastic activities in the elementary grades including curriculum, assessment, and administration concerns. Emphasis on designing appropriate programs and activities and teaching methodology. Use of class discussions, presentations, small group and peer teaching. Includes fifteen hours of observation-practicum in the schools. Students will need to provide their own transportation to their public school practicum.','KIN 111',''),
(365,2025,25,101,'5','Sociological Thinking','Mary Olson',1,'SOC',NULL,'Do you wonder why people do the things they do?  Why society works as it does?  Ever think the world is “unfair”?  Sociologists study people in the world, looking at patterns, at differences, at inequalities.  Thinking sociologically is like “entering a new and unfamiliar society--one in which things are no longer what they seem.”  It creates “culture shock without geographical displacement.”  This course requires us to look at society with a new perspective, to question our taken-for-granted assumptions, to investigate people\'s actions, and to explore the organization of society.  It provides a basis for being engaged citizens, thinking about social alternatives, and imagining possibilities for social justice. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(366,2025,25,754,'Adjunct Spring','Theatre Administration HEIGHTS','Scott Olinger',0.25,'THE',NULL,'This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(367,2025,25,225,'8','Money and Banking','Todd Knoop',1,'ECB',NULL,'The role of financial institutions and financial assets in macroeconomic activity. The stock market, money markets, monetary policy, money supply and demand, interest rates, inflation, international financial markets, and the International Monetary Fund.','ECB 101, STA 201, MAT 348','Social Science'),
(368,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Spring','Saxophone: Woodwind Instruments','Ryan Smith',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(369,2025,18,264,'5','Physical Theatre','Patrick DuLaney',1,'THE',NULL,'Students will be introduced to a variety of methodologies for a practice of physical theatre.  Students will gain an introductory knowledge of such approaches as Viewpoints, Grotowski, Mime and Commedia Dell\'arte.  Students should expect to MOVE in this class, but all levels of physical fitness and experience are encouraged.','THE 115','Fine Arts'),
(370,2025,25,279,'4','Personality Psychology','Samantha Heiman',1,'PSY',NULL,'Survey of major research, issues, debates, and theoretical approaches to understanding personality, including humanistic, learning, cognitive, dispositional, and psychodynamic theories as well as a thorough consideration of the person/situation debate, psychological traits, and the Big 5 Model of personality. This course emphasizes a critical understanding of the utility of these theories and models based on empirical research findings. The course includes discussion (and completion) of many ways to assess personality to help students better understand how personality is measured and whether these assessments are capable of providing the answers psychologists, individuals, and businesses seek out by employing these tools.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Encounter, Writing Encounter'),
(371,2025,18,303,'8','Seconday Art Methods','Jill Heinrich',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course is designed to help prepare students to be effective teachers of art at the secondary school level.  The practicum will allow students to observe and teach in the high school art classroom and examine the stages of artistic development and appropriate art lessons and teaching strategies.  Consequently, students will be in conversation about the particulars of teaching various artistic mediums in the high school setting.  This course is conducted at the practicum site. Transportation to and from the practicum site is the responsibility of the student. Course is graded Credit/No Credit.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240',NULL),
(372,2025,20,103,'7','Beginning Spanish III','Juana New Gavidia',1,'SPA',NULL,'Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development.','SPA 102, SPA 102C','Language'),
(373,2025,18,755,'Adjunct Spring','Dance Performance','Amy Simonson',0.25,'THE',NULL,'Dance Performance is a course open to students with various dance backgrounds and levels who seek to enhance their technical and performance skills beyond the block format.  Class will focus around warm-up, diagonal exercises, and movement compositions.  Techniques to be explored in this course include, contemporary modern, jazz, and classical ballet.  This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Ingenuity in Action, Creative Expression'),
(374,2025,25,798,'Adjunct Fall','Half Recital','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'25 minutes of music. Required of Music Performance majors. Available to any student with approval of the Department. No alternative grade option. A pre-recital hearing is required. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Ingenuity in Action, Creative Expression'),
(375,2025,25,210,'6','Music Theory II','Jama Stilwell',1,'MUS',NULL,'Continuation of MUS 110. Topics include the harmonic progression, triads in inversion, non-chord tones, and an introduction to phrases, periods, and their role in creating musical form. ','MUS 110','Fine Arts'),
(376,2025,15,305,'8','Costume Design FEE1','Jenny Kelchen',1,'THE',850,'Exploration of the role of the costume designer in the design and production process. Building upon skills learned in THE 108 and through script and character analysis, students begin to develop the visual design of clothing for a play using line, color, silhouette, texture, etc. Project work focuses on developing research and rendering skills, as well as budgeting and allocation of costume technology assets. Alternate years (alternates with THE 267). A fee may be charged during years in which a portion of the course takes place in Chicago. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog.','THE 108','Fine Arts, Chicago'),
(377,2025,18,317,'8','Mthds-Elementary Science and Soc Studies','Madison Parker',1,'EDU',NULL,'Current elementary school methods in the teaching of natural science and social studies. Special emphasis on the development of interdisciplinary methods, the development of curricular units, lesson design, computer applications, student assessment, and classroom management. Thirty hours of observation-practicum in the schools. Students must provide their own transportation. This course must be taken PRIOR to student teaching. No alternative grade option.  This course requires an in-person practicum experience at the school. Students doing online learning are not eligible to take this course.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240',''),
(378,2025,25,121,'7','Communication in Education','Kerry Bostwick',1,'INT',NULL,'A focus on communication demands for educators provides the context for this course in which students will give prepared speeches and group presentations intended for such audiences as parents, community members, educational colleagues, and other education stakeholders.  Scenarios for class activities will feature issues of cross-cultural communication, nonverbal behavior, and virtual communication media appropriate for school-home community information sharing.This course is intended for students interested in pursuing a major in education. Credit/No Credit (CR)','',''),
(379,2025,25,485,'6','Senior Capstone Project','Ann Cannon',1,'MAT',NULL,'Students will conduct research on a subject or problem that they have selected and that has been approved by a Mathematics faculty member, who will serve as their advisor for this project. The work will culminate in a paper and a public presentation.In addition to consulting with the instructor of the course and their capstone advisor on the final written project, students will spend class time presenting their progress to classmates peers, sharing and developing ideas, answering questions, and overcoming difficulties arising in their research. Prerequisite: MAT 502 Capstone Preparation. No alternate grade option.','MAT 502','Writing Intensive'),
(380,2025,25,308,'6','20th Century Phil: Phenom to Post-Modern','Megan Altman',1,'PHI',NULL,'Now that it has drawn to a close, we can begin to make sense of philosophy in the 20th Century. What makes it distinctive? Which topics and figures dominated it and why? How does it carry forth ideas from the 19th Century, and what might it be pointing towards in the future? In this course, we will focus on Continental thought which arises primarily in continental Europe, rather than Analytic philosophy which is more common in Anglo-American departments. We will read about major philosophical movements from the 20th century, including phenomenology, existentialism and black existentialism, feminist phenomenology, and postmodernism as represented by thinkers such as Martin Heidegger, Simone de Beauvoir, Franz Fanon, Hannah Arendt, and Jacques Derrida. Among other key topics to be covered, we will focus on existence, anxiety, death, and meaning.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(381,2025,25,240,'3','Education and Culture','Sarah Doyle',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course examines American core culture and the essential role that public education plays in that culture.  Specifically, it explores the socio-civic mandate which requires schools to prepare students for participation in a democratic society; in doing so, students are encouraged to understand and be sensitive to the values, beliefs, lifestyles and attitudes of individuals and diverse groups found in a pluralistic society.  Not open to juniors and seniors without instructor permission. No alternate grade option.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(382,2025,16,318,'8','Topics: Comedia','Patrick DuLaney',1,'THE',NULL,'Prerequisite: THE 115','THE 115','Fine Arts'),
(383,2025,25,256,'6','Italian Renaissance Art','Chris Penn-Goetsch',1,'ART',NULL,'The visual arts of Italy from the late medieval period through the end of the sixteenth century. Artists covered include Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, Raphael, Donatello, and Titian. Elective for Medieval and Early Modern Studies majors. No alternative grade option. [AH]','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
