(393,2025,25,214,'3','Tectonics','Emily Walsh',1,'GEO',NULL,'An examination of plate tectonic processes on Earth. Topics will include the building of mountains, rifting of ocean basins, the structure of Earth\'s interior, paleomagnetism, and the driving forces behind plate movement. Also includes introduction to structural geology and field mapping. Includes several field trips.','GEO 105, GEO 106, GEO 107, GEO 111, GEO 122, GEO 125, GEO 130, GEO 160','Science'),
(394,2025,99,711,'Adjunct Spring','Chamber Ensembles Horn','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(395,2025,25,201,'5','Data Structures','Lauren Jepsen',1,'CSC',NULL,'Students will learn how to create arrays, linked lists, binary search trees, hash tables. They will learn to use these data structures in the solutions of problems. They will see how the selection of the right data structure allows faster and easier storage, retrieval, and manipulation of data.','CSC 140, CSC 144',''),
(396,2025,25,761,'Adjunct Fall','Piano','Jessica Monnier',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(397,2025,50,0,'Adjunct Spring','Pending Internship','Registrar Staff',1,'INTRN',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, internship. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the internship block.','',''),
(398,2025,25,111,'7','Dynamic Earth','Rhawn Denniston',1,'GEO',NULL,'The earth as a dynamic body whose materials and structures are continually being modified by the interactions of the geological processes; considers interrelationships between geological processes and human activity. Fieldtrips as weather permits. Not open to students previously enrolled in GEO 114.','','Science'),
(399,2025,15,108,'3','Costume Construction','Jenny Kelchen',1,'THE',75,'Introduction to costume construction technology, including sewing, pattern reading and draping, through classroom and laboratory work. A brief survey of dress throughout history and introductory costume design project are included. Students are required to help in the construction of costumes for an upcoming Theatre Department production. This course has a materials fee of approximately $75 per student.','','Fine Arts'),
(400,2025,25,230,'5','Quan Research Mthds in Political Science','Megan Goldberg',1,'POL',NULL,'In this course, we’ll learn how to turn the puzzles, events, and stories we encounter in the political world into quantitative political science research. We’ll build a foundation by carefully considering what types of questions we can and cannot answer with quantitative data, how we translate abstract concepts into data, and how that translation affects the conclusions that we draw. From there, we will move on to how we can think clearly with data, and avoid some of the most common problems that plague quantitative social science work. Some of the topics covered in this course include the potential outcomes framework, randomized experiments, instrumental variables, regression discontinuity designs, and difference in difference methods.This course may count toward the International Relations minor.','STA 201','Social Science'),
(401,2025,25,420,'6','Student Teaching II','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','EDU 410','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(402,2025,25,772,'Adjunct Spring','Violin: String Instruments','Andrew Gentzsch',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(403,2025,50,0,'1','Pending Internship','Registrar Staff',1,'INTRN',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, internship. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the internship block.','',''),
(404,2025,25,328,'5','Exercise Psychology & Comm/Behav Health','Christi Johnson',1,'KIN',NULL,'Examination of theory and current research regarding the promotion of health as related to physical activity; including psychological, social, community-based, policy, and cultural influences. Topics include psychological and emotional effects of exercise, barriers and facilitators for physical activity, factors in exercise avoidance, adoption, and adherence, cognitive, behavioral, social, and policy-oriented change strategies for exercise, and consideration of gender, ethnicity, and special needs populations.','KIN 111, CPH 115, BIO 208','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Encounter, Writing Encounter'),
(405,2025,20,101,'1','Beginning Spanish I','Alyssa Selmer',1,'SPA',NULL,'Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development.','','Language'),
(406,2025,15,483,'4','Senior Seminar','Kerry Bostwick',1,'EDU',NULL,'Students complete this capstone course upon conclusion of their student teaching.  Involves critical examination of current educational controversies, reform ideas, ethical considerations, legal questions, and administrative problems facing modern American education. Students complete a major research project and professional presentation. Credit/No Credit (CR). ','EDU 430, EDU 470, ACM 966','Teacher Preparation'),
(407,2025,25,752,'Adjunct Fall','Percussion Instruments','Virginia Armstrong',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(408,2025,25,278,'6','Adolescence','Katelyn Pitcher',1,'PSY',NULL,'Investigation of research on biological, cognitive, and cultural influences on adolescent development. Includes the impact of family, peers, school, media, and work, as well as identity, gender, and sexuality development. Also includes a discussion of problem behaviors (e.g., eating disorders, juvenile delinquency, alcohol use/abuse) often associated with adolescence. Course involves application of research findings to individual cases.','PSY 161','Social Science'),
(409,2025,20,102,'1','Beginning Spanish II','Michael Mosier',1,'SPA',NULL,'Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development. ','SPA 101, SPA 101C','Language'),
(410,2025,25,201,'3','Introduction to Literary Studies','Katy Stavreva',1,'ENG',NULL,'Transporting us across time and cultures, taking us out of ourselves and into new worlds—what a wild ride literature takes us on! What strategies of reading and analysis can help us understand what it does—and how it works its spell on readers? The introduction to the English major will approach these questions through tactics for reading, analyzing and interpreting works of literature and their cultural moment, including the illuminating work of close reading. We’ll focus on understanding literary conventions, writers who challenge them, multiple genres or forms of writing—as well as hybrid ones, and will look into critical inquiry and theory that open up our reading worlds. We will develop our writing and research skills as we explore a variety of texts, including ones from diverse cultural moments and historical periods. \r\nCheck with Self-Service for the specific texts to be explored in your section.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(411,2025,25,131,'6','Intro to Engineering Design','Danielle Grimes',1,'EGR',NULL,'The goal of engineering is to solve problems faced by society. In this course, students will learn how the engineering process works: defining the problem; conducting background research; constructing design criteria; evaluating and testing designs, and developing and testing prototypes. Students will also discuss and critically analyze papers discussing ethical issues that arise both during the design process as well as the interaction between technology and society. This course also emphasizes the importance of effective communication for engineers: students will be required to present their own reports (both oral and written) as well as critiquing other papers.','',''),
(412,2025,15,326,'2','Women in Renaissance& Reformation Europe','Michelle Herder',1,'HIS',NULL,'This course examines the experiences of women during the tumultuous Renaissance and Reformation period (c. 1400-1700). Questions to be examined include: How did women participate in these movements, and how were they affected by them? What ideas about women were debated in this period? How did women’s experiences change during this period? In addition to reading historical documents, in the course we will read, evaluate, and critique modern scholarship on early modern women.','Junior standing or permission of instructor','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(413,2025,20,111,'1','How Do We Know What We Know? FYS','Danielle Grimes',1,'INT',NULL,'This common first year seminar explores how we know what we know and the various ways and conventions by which we communicate knowledge. For example, how do we take in and evaluate information? How do our brains make deliberate and/or rapid decisions? How does our knowledge both individually and societally change over time? What does it mean to know something? How do we consider perspectives different from our own? Learning requires raising questions that stem from reasoning, curiosity, and empathy. Through questioning, we become informed citizens and scholars. Through careful reading, creative and critical thinking, speaking and writing, we will engage with a variety of texts from many genres and disciplinary perspectives. Your instructor will serve as a guide along this path by encouraging you to consider different perspectives on and ways of knowing as you start to identify areas for your own growth as a college student.','',''),
(414,2025,25,110,'4','Introduction to Management','Tony Rose',1,'ECB',NULL,'Introduction to Management examines the theory, techniques, and applications of management systems. Planning, organizing, leading, and controlling are issues addressed. It includes a detailed study of how firms determine their main objectives, plan their strategies, organize, motivate, and lead their employees to achieve those goals as well as control their operations to evaluate and correct their actions. Specific topics include environmental influences, organization design and structure, motivation, leadership, ethics, innovation, total quality management, etc. This course will help you understand and analyze how managers can formulate and implement strategies effectively, leverage values, build an engaging and motivating workplace, and manage risk and ambiguity.','','Social Science'),
(415,2025,15,395,'8','Human Services Practicum & Seminar','Kris Robbins',1,'PSY',NULL,'Supervised full-time internship in a human service context and a weekly seminar. Group discussions of current issues in the field such as cultural and gender diversity, ethics, professional practice challenges, and the role of research in practice. Students must provide their own transportation and purchase professional liability insurance through the American Psychological Association. Course is completed for credit (CR), not letter grades. No alternative grade option. Students who wish to pursue an internship outside the Eastern Iowa area will need to discuss this with the instructor prior to the class beginning allowances will be made on a case by case basis. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action categories, Civic Engagement or Professional Exploration. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','Psychology courses, declared Psychology major, junior standing','Social Science'),
(416,2025,15,325,'6','Health Education Methods','Lewis Kanyiba',1,'KIN',NULL,'An introduction to curriculum development, instruction, and assessment in health\r\neducation as guided by the Iowa’s and National Health Education Standards and\r\nPerformance Indicators for preK-12. This participatory course primarily focuses on\r\nutilization of current local data and policy to develop, practice, and achieve proficiency\r\nin skills related to chosen health and well-being needs/topics. Students will explore\r\ntheir own health and well-being needs through personal behavior change projects.\r\nStudents will further demonstrate proficiency in curriculum delivery and reflective\r\nlearning through group advocacy projects to be presented to an audience of choice\r\n(e.g., preK-12 schools, college campuses, community centers, etc.). Students will need to provide their own transportation to their public school practicum.','Sophomore Standing','Social Science, Writing Intensive'),
(417,2025,25,485,'6','Senior Capstone Project','Ann Cannon',1,'STA',NULL,'Students will continue work on the project identified in STA 502 with their capstone advisor. The work will culminate in a paper and a public presentation.  In addition to consulting with their capstone advisor and the instructor of the course, students will spend class time presenting their progress to classmates, sharing and developing ideas, asking and answering questions, and overcoming difficulties arising in their research. No alternate grade option.','STA 502','Writing Intensive'),
(418,2025,25,771,'Adjunct Fall','Cello: String Instruments','James Ellis',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(419,2025,25,328,'7','The Early Modern Globe','Michelle Herder',1,'HIS',NULL,'In the 1500s, the world became interconnected as never before. People and goods crossed oceans and cultures, disrupting both the Old World and the New. Indian princes and Chinese officials bought New World gems and metals from European middlemen; ordinary people could afford imported foods, textiles, and china. New trade routes and gunpowder challenged or destroyed old state structures and built new ones. In this course, we will trace the movement of people, objects, and goods around the world, from indigenous miners, farmers, and artisans, through the hands of merchants and smugglers, to their destinations at luxurious courts or common people\'s households. The course explores the global impact of early colonization, migration, and enslavement, and how the patterns developed between 1500 and 1700 paved the way for the modern world.','Any 100-level History course, or permission of instructor','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(420,2025,20,111,'1','How Do We Know What We Know? FYS','Collin O\'Leary',1,'INT',NULL,'This common first year seminar explores how we know what we know and the various ways and conventions by which we communicate knowledge. For example, how do we take in and evaluate information? How do our brains make deliberate and/or rapid decisions? How does our knowledge both individually and societally change over time? What does it mean to know something? How do we consider perspectives different from our own? Learning requires raising questions that stem from reasoning, curiosity, and empathy. Through questioning, we become informed citizens and scholars. Through careful reading, creative and critical thinking, speaking and writing, we will engage with a variety of texts from many genres and disciplinary perspectives. Your instructor will serve as a guide along this path by encouraging you to consider different perspectives on and ways of knowing as you start to identify areas for your own growth as a college student.','',''),
(421,2025,20,111,'1','How Do We Know What We Know? FYS','Isaac Winkler',1,'INT',NULL,'This common first year seminar explores how we know what we know and the various ways and conventions by which we communicate knowledge. For example, how do we take in and evaluate information? How do our brains make deliberate and/or rapid decisions? How does our knowledge both individually and societally change over time? What does it mean to know something? How do we consider perspectives different from our own? Learning requires raising questions that stem from reasoning, curiosity, and empathy. Through questioning, we become informed citizens and scholars. Through careful reading, creative and critical thinking, speaking and writing, we will engage with a variety of texts from many genres and disciplinary perspectives. Your instructor will serve as a guide along this path by encouraging you to consider different perspectives on and ways of knowing as you start to identify areas for your own growth as a college student.','',''),
(422,2025,18,301,'4','Advanced Grammar and Composition','Juana New Gavidia',1,'SPA',NULL,'Intensive practice in writing in Spanish in combination with a study of Spanish grammar that concentrates on those aspects of the language which are challenging for the advanced student. Emphasis on expanding vocabulary and developing writing fluency. Required of all Spanish majors. ','SPA 205, SPA 206, SPA 265','Writing Encounter, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(423,2025,25,251,'2','Introduction to Entrepreneurship','Tony Rose',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course provides an introduction to the study of how business enterprises are created and revitalized. Included will be an overview of the financial, marketing, organizational, and managerial tools that entrepreneurs use when shaping an enterprise. In addition, this course will introduce the topic of social entrepreneurship, in which organizations are created that not only generate a return for the entrepreneur, but also address significant social problems such as poverty alleviation or environmental protection.','',''),
(424,2025,25,781,'Adjunct Spring','Voice','Lynne Rothrock',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(425,2025,20,103,'2','Beginning Spanish III','Juana New Gavidia',1,'SPA',NULL,'Essentials of grammar stressing skills in understanding, speaking, reading, and writing with classroom activities promoting conversational skills. Short readings for cultural awareness and vocabulary development.','SPA 102, SPA 102C','Language'),
(426,2025,25,732,'Adjunct Spring','French Horn: Brass Instruments','Peter Kortenkamp',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(427,2025,25,332,'7','Human Rights','David Yamanishi',1,'POL',NULL,'Practices and characteristics of governments and non-governmental actors that abuse and protect human rights, history of the concept and treatment of rights, justifications for the protection of rights, differences between categories of rights, prospects for the improved protection of rights through international and domestic action. Alternate years.','Junior Standing','Social Science, International Relations & Comparative Government, Writing Encounter'),
(428,2025,25,420,'2','Student Teaching II','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements.','EDU 410','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(429,2025,25,182,'Adjunct Spring','Public Policy','Megan Goldberg',1,'POL',NULL,'Introduction to the policy-making process, to the basics of public policy analysis, and to the substance of selected policy debates.','','Social Science, American Politics & Public Policy'),
(430,2025,25,708,'Adjunct Fall','Instrumental Techniques Guitar','Tom Nothnagle',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'Development of basic performing techniques. Study and evaluation of procedures and materials for elementary and intermediate instrumental teaching. No alternate grade option.','',''),
(431,2025,25,483,'5','Research Seminar','David Yamanishi',1,'POL',NULL,'Each student will choose a topic within politics to explore through group discussion and peer review, presentations, and a paper that critically reviews existing research to advance an argument. No alternative grade option. ','Politics major with junior standing and three 300-level Politics classes other than internships','Social Science'),
(432,2025,25,212,'5','Social Analytics','Santhi Hejeebu',1,'ECB',NULL,'In a tech savvy society, personal and business relationships often originate on-line. Computer-mediated relationships are typically represented as networks. This course introduces the science of networks, integrating ideas from sociology, economics, and mathematics. We will learn how to identify important people and relationships within a social network. We will also learn how to predict the formation of new links among members of a social network. The course also explores how information and economic behavior, such as viral marketing ads, travel across a network. Throughout the class, students will visualize networks and explore course concepts through data acquired from popular social media websites such as Twitter.','STA 201, STA 348','Social Science'),
(433,2025,25,430,'4','Exercise Testing & Prescription','Kristi Meyer',1,'KIN',NULL,'Practical application of physiological principles related to the assessment of functional physical capacity and the prescription of exercise for healthy adult populations, based upon American College of Sports Medicine (ACSM) health-related fitness recommendations. Development of practical skills and professionalism for performing fitness assessments, including: the pre-participation screening; heart rate and blood pressure at rest and during exercise; and assessments of body composition, cardiorespiratory fitness, muscular strength, and flexibility. Includes interpretation of health-related fitness assessment results and the prescription of appropriate fitness programs for improving musculoskeletal strength and flexibility, cardiorespiratory fitness, and weight loss.','KIN 207, BIO 207, KIN 208, KIN 315, KIN 328, KIN 329',''),
(434,2025,25,762,'Adjunct Spring','Piano','James Martin',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(435,2025,25,277,'8','Child Development','Katelyn Pitcher',1,'PSY',NULL,'Physiological, cognitive, social, and cultural influences on development from conception through middle childhood. Emphasis on building an integrated picture of child development and an appreciation of how theory and data can be applied to the analysis of practical issues. Fifteen to twenty hours of observation in daycares/preschools. Students must provide their own transportation.','PSY 161','Social Science'),
(436,2025,25,102,'4','Microeconomics','James Goodenberger',1,'ECB',NULL,'Basic microeconomic analysis of consumer choice, the business firm, and resource markets in labor, capital, and land. Analysis and critique of government policy in problem areas such as monopoly power and government regulations and expenditures.','two years of algebra in high school','Social Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(437,2025,18,305,'8','Secondary Math Methods','Jill Heinrich',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course is focused on the practice of teaching mathematics.  It will offer students opportunities to observe, experiment with, and evaluate specific instructional methods for mathematics and discuss the importance of balancing theory with practice.  Specifically, this course is designed around three primary domains of teaching mathematics: providing instructional explanations of mathematics, facilitating small-group cooperative problem solving, and orchestrating whole-class mathematical discussions. This course is conducted at the practicum site.  Transportation to and from the practicum site is the responsibility of the student. Course is graded Credit/No Credit.','EDU 301, EDU 328','Credit/No Credit'),
(438,2025,25,512,'Adjunct Fall','Professional Practice','Ajit Chavan',0.25,'CSC',NULL,'Each student will gain experience in the iterative development of software through all stages of development, in presentations of a project to their peers, and in the review of their peers’ projects. Success will require application of knowledge and skills acquired in several core and elective courses. This practice solving problems like those encountered in industry and advanced study will prepare students for the challenges and opportunities that await them after graduation.\r\nStudents should consult with an advisor in the department before beginning the course. In this course, students should plan on improving a project begun and substantially completed in another course. That other course may be taken concurrently. The course involves meeting twice each term for a total of 12 hours per semester and approximately 24 hours of work outside of class. Is repeatable once for credit. ','CSC 140, CSC 144, CSC 218, CSC 301',''),
(439,2025,25,221,'8','Ecology','Josh Otten',1,'BIO',NULL,'Ecology is the study of connections among individuals and species, and with their abiotic environment. Modern ecology includes natural history observations, but also integrates evolutionary thinking, biology, geology, behavior, physiology, physics, chemistry and many other fields. We will use a combination of field observations/research, lectures, reading and writing to explore various aspects of ecology. By examining both local patterns and distant examples at different scales, we will quite literally gain a view of the trees, the forest, and the surrounding landscape.','BIO 142, BIO 235','Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(440,2025,50,0,'Adjunct Spring','Pending Individual Project','Registrar Staff',1,'PROJ',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, individual project. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the individual project block.','',''),
(441,2025,25,410,'5','Student Teaching I','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','All 200- and 300-level Education courses and approval of the Education Department','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(442,2025,4,355,'8','Contemporary Songwriting II','Christopher Nakielski',1,'MUS',0,'Building upon the foundational skills developed in MUS 155 Contemporary Songwriting I, this course delves into advanced songwriting techniques and explores the practical aspects of the contemporary music industry. Students will refine their individual songwriting voices, experiment with diverse genres and production styles, and develop a deeper understanding of the business of songwriting. The culmination of this course will involve a trip to a renowned Chicago Recording Studio.  Offered concurrently with MUS 155.','MUS 155','Fine Arts'),
(443,2025,20,487,'6','Senior Thesis','Alex McKenzie',1,'ART',NULL,'A substantial capstone project to be completed during the senior year. Studio majors conceive, create, and mount an exhibition of a new body of work. Art history majors research an art historical problem, write a research paper, prepare an abstract, and provide a public presentation of their work with the goal of creating an original contribution to the discipline. An oral defense is required for either major. No alternative grade option. The Studio Art section is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. The Art History section is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Research. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','ART 483, ART 392','Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression, Ingenuity in Action category, Research'),
(444,2025,25,110,'7','Archaeology','John Doershuk',1,'ARC',NULL,'Intensive introductory-level exploration of how archaeologists use a systematic scientific approach to investigate the past. Specifics on selected past cultures will be presented although this course is not intended to be a comprehensive overview of human prehistory. Students will learn about (1) research methods for the collection of archaeological data; (2) techniques developed for interpreting archaeological site formation, relative and chronometric dating, and artifact analyses; (3) a brief history of archaeological inquiry; and (4) essential theoretical underpinnings of major archaeological paradigms. Alternate years.','',''),
(445,2025,25,208,'3','Human Systems Physiology & Anatlomy II','Kristi Meyer',1,'BIO',NULL,'Part II in a two part series of a fundamental study of the complementarity of human anatomical structure and physiological function of the integumentary, endocrine, nervous, muscular, cardiovascular, respiratory, digestive, and renal systems. Special emphasis on the connective tissue and skeletal system physiology, identification of major musculoskeletal structures (bones and bony landmarks, origins and insertions for major muscles, muscle groups, major tendinous/ligamentous structures), joint movements and muscle actions.  Practical application of anatomical and neuromuscular principles to human movement via a kinematic analysis of a motor skill. Inclusion of experiential learning through laboratory activities. Previously listed as KIN 208.','BIO 207, KIN 207',NULL),
(446,2025,25,754,'Adjunct Spring','Theatre Administration MOCK','Scott Olinger',0.25,'THE',NULL,'This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(447,2025,25,731,'Adjunct Fall','Trumpet: Brass Instruments','Desmond Cervantez',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(448,2025,18,301,'2','Secondary Curriculum & Instruction','Jill Heinrich',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course is designed to provide secondary teacher education candidates with an opportunity to study, reflect, question, and become knowledgeable about instructional methods while applying and practicing these methods in a collaborative and constructive setting. Major topics include: assessment of student learning, classroom management, curriculum development, and instructional technology. This course requires an in-person practicum experience at the school. Students doing online learning are not eligible to take this course. This course must be taken PRIOR to student teaching.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240','None'),
(449,2025,25,230,'8','Exceptional Learner','Corrine Neville',1,'EDU',NULL,'An introduction to understanding the diversity of learners in K-12 classrooms and how differentiated teaching methods and materials are essential to create a more inclusive and equitable environment for all students. The major focus of the course will be identifying the strengths and challenges of students to increase engagement and raise achievement through varied approaches to teaching culturally and linguistically diverse learners and students with documented needs.  Not open to juniors and seniors without permission of instructor.  No alternate grade option.Fifteen practicum hours required in the schools. Personal transportation will be needed for two separate days in this course.','','Social Science'),
(450,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Fall','Bassoon: Woodwind Instruments','Sara Remoy',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(451,2025,99,716,'Adjunct Fall','Concert Band','Drew Bonner',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(452,2025,25,260,'2','Modern Art','Michael Feinberg',1,'ART',NULL,'Investigation of the development of Modernism and its demise during the second half of the twentieth century. Multiple styles are discussed from the late nineteenth century to 1960. No alternative grade option. [AH]','','Humanities, Writing Encounter, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(453,2025,28,141,'2','Introductory Physics I','Mazhar Iqbal',1,'PHY',NULL,'Non-calculus treatment of elementary physics covering the topics of mechanics, relativity, and waves. Emphasis on problem-solving.','2 years of high school algebra, including trigonometry.','Science'),
(454,2025,20,101,'4','Beginning French I','Devan Baty',1,'FRE',NULL,'French 101- FRE 103 develop students\' linguistic and cultural proficiency. Coursework covers speaking, listening, reading and writing in French. The French language will be used to communicate during 90% or more of class time by both the instructor and students. Successful completion of the beginning-level language course sequence prepares students to function in a variety of authentic communicative situations within a French speaking context and to become life-long language learners. All French language classes, from the beginning to the advanced level, also develop students\' awareness and understanding of cultural phenomena in the Francophone world. French 101 is designed for true beginners in the language. Students are introduced to the standard conventions of French pronunciation, grammar, and vocabulary, and focus is placed on building students\' foundation in linguistic proficiency through exercises in speaking, writing, listening and reading. Students learn how to introduce and describe themselves and others, including friends and family. They learn about geography in the French and Francophone world, how to give directions and describe the weather, and how to discuss leisure activities, and travel.','','Language'),
(455,2026,25,752,'Adjunct Spring','Percussion Instruments','Virginia Armstrong',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(456,2025,25,385,'7','Engineering Design Project','Derin Sherman',1,'EGR',NULL,'Students propose a real-world engineering problem, then devise a novel solution to that problem.  Specific projects will be chosen in an area of the student’s interest with prior consultation with the instructor.  Course work includes the design, construction, and testing of the project, a comprehensive written report, oral presentation, and reflection paper.  Students should take this course during their final year at Cornell. No Alternate Grade option.  Senior  standing or permission of instructor.','EGR 231, EGR 271, EGR 311, EGR 331, EGR 332, EGR 336, EGR 341, EGR 346, EGR 352, EGR 361, EGR 362','Senior'),
(457,2025,25,328,'6','Human Resource Management','Patricia Helland',1,'ECB',NULL,'With the transition to a knowledge-based workforce, designing and implementing effective human capital systems is essential. This class will utilize cases and hands on simulations to facilitate understanding of the leaders’ role in implementing and utilizing effective human capital systems. We will focus on the processes of talent acquisition, learning and development, performance management, and career/succession planning and understand how these human capital processes impact both the success of the business/organizational strategy and the engagement of people. Through the study of human capital, we find that the traditional Human Resources role has expanded to include not only implementation of controls and services for internal customers, but also the importance of the partnership among leaders, employees and human resources professionals.','PSY 274, STA 201','Social Science'),
(458,2025,18,240,'5','Manufacturing Processes','Danielle Grimes',1,'EGR',NULL,'Explores the processes and decisions involved in manufacturing through project-based learning. Topics include machining, injection molding, casting, welding, and additive manufacturing, and students will work in teams on project management. Emphasizes material and process selection for real-world applications. Students will use the computer lab for 3D design and will learn to operate computerized numerical control (CNC) machines and 3D printers to design and build real-life objects.','EGR 131, EGR 231',''),
(459,2025,25,792,'Adjunct Spring','Flute: Woodwind Instruments','Victoria Bishop',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(460,2025,12,261,'6','Tpcs: Comparative Education Europe FEE1','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',25,'Travel to Germany and Spain, spending time in schools in both countries to understand their structures, policies and practices in comparison to the school systems of the US. Gain insights into the different socal, cultural, and historical foundations of each country’s school systems. Students will spend time in an elementary school in the Lower Saxony region of Germany while staying in the quaint German city of Verden, outside of Hamburg and south of Bremen. Students will explore Hamburg as a part of their German experience. Students will travel to Madrid, Spain, where they will spend time in the charter/bilingual schools of Madrid. During the time in Spain, students will explore sites in and around the city of Madrid, using public transportation to access the city and also taking a trip to see areas such Toledo, Segovia, and other Spanish sites. While German or Spanish proficiency is not required for this course, students should be comfortable with practicums in both country’s schools and be willing to be uncomfortable due to possible language barriers at times. Total course cost: $4,950. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog. This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','EDU 200-level courses','Social Science'),
(461,2025,25,273,'5','Topics: Arts of Latin America/Caribbean','Michael Feinberg',1,'ART',NULL,'This course explores the art and architecture of Latin America and the Caribbean from the late 15th century to the early 18th century. Beginning with visual materials that predate contact with Europeans, students will investigate how colonization and empire profoundly altered artistic production in these regions. Particular attention will be given to artists of Indigenous and multiethnic descent.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(462,2025,25,772,'Adjunct Fall','Viola: String Instruments','Michelle Bennett',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(463,2025,25,752,'Adjunct Spring','Percussion Instruments','Thomas Mackey',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(464,2025,25,364,'7','Crime, Deviance and Society','Tori Barnes-Brus',1,'SOC',NULL,'This course investigates the ways in which deviance and social control operate in daily life and emphasizes the social construction of deviance. Course will explore the ways in which power and inequality shape social conceptions of deviance and expectations for socially controlling behaviors and the ways that privilege and inequality shape deviance and social control at structural and interactional levels, with specific attention to race, class, and gender. We will investigate social stigma facing poor and marginalized groups and the ways in which criminal justice could be more \"just. Course will situate discussions within various theoretical contexts to help us better understand the way deviance and social control are embedded in our society. This course may count toward the SOC, CPH, and RES major.','SOC 101, CPH 115','Social Science, Writing Encounter'),
(465,2025,99,720,'Adjunct Fall','Steel Drum Ensemble','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(466,2025,25,799,'Adjunct Fall','Full Recital','MUS Dept Chair Staff',1,'MUS',NULL,'50 minutes of music; usually performed in the senior year. Required of Music Performance majors. Available to any student with approval of the Department. No alternate grade option. A pre-recital hearing is required. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Ingenuity in Action, Creative Expression'),
(467,2025,200,103,'Adjunct Spring','Experiential Learning Off Campus Study','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Creative Expression experiences are opportunities for students to explore their creative potential and develop as artists. Activities in this category are focused on the conceptualization and execution of creative work. These experiences should emphasize exploring the student’s creative process and aesthetic choices. In addition, sharing one\'s work is an important part of the creative process, which calls upon the artist to participate in a community of other artists. Creative work therefore should be presented, published, performed, or exhibited in some form.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(468,2025,25,752,'Adjunct Fall','Costumes and Make-up SISTERS','Jenny Kelchen',0.25,'THE',NULL,'This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(469,2025,5,485,'6','Biological Problems','Josh Otten',1,'BIO',NULL,'Investigation of a biological problem, including a review of the literature, collection and interpretation of data, and writing of a research report. May be repeated once for credit. Intended for seniors or advanced juniors, this is a capstone experience for Biology and BMB majors. Arrangements must be made with the instructor before registering. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation for Ingenuity in Action. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application. ','BIO 210, BIO 221','Science, Writing Encounter'),
(470,2025,25,513,'Adjunct Fall','Advanced Athletic Traning Practicum(1/2)','Kristi Meyer',0.5,'KIN',NULL,'Provides an advanced supervised practical experience in the prevention, evaluation, treatment, management, and rehabilitation of athletic injuries and illness. Participation in the administrative aspects of an athletic training program. May be taken over multiple terms. Maximum number of credits allowed: 2 credits. (1/2 credit per enrollment) ','Must have at least one year experience as a Cornell Sports Medicine Assistant.','CR'),
(471,2025,25,224,'8','Sedimentology & Stratigraphy','Andrew Walters',1,'GEO',NULL,'Sedimentary processes and the stratigraphic record. Basics of correlation, particle transport, and facies models with emphasis on relative dating and paleoenvironmental reconstruction. Topics include sedimentary structures, basin analysis, and sea level change. Hand specimen and microscopic study of sedimentary rocks.','GEO 105, GEO 106, GEO 107, GEO 111, GEO 122, GEO 125, GEO 130, GEO 160','Laboratory Science'),
(472,2025,25,101,'4','Sociological Thinking','Mary Olson',1,'SOC',NULL,'Do you wonder why people do the things they do?  Why society works as it does?  Ever think the world is “unfair”?  Sociologists study people in the world, looking at patterns, at differences, at inequalities.  Thinking sociologically is like “entering a new and unfamiliar society--one in which things are no longer what they seem.”  It creates “culture shock without geographical displacement.”  This course requires us to look at society with a new perspective, to question our taken-for-granted assumptions, to investigate people\'s actions, and to explore the organization of society.  It provides a basis for being engaged citizens, thinking about social alternatives, and imagining possibilities for social justice. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(473,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Spring','Bassoon: Woodwind Instruments','Sara Remoy',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(474,2025,25,279,'7','Topics: Graves, Games, Gladiators FEE1','John Gruber-Miller, Chris Hoklotubbe',1,'CLA',4650,'Embark on an immersive journey through the heart of the Roman Empire, where history comes alive amid towering monuments, crumbling ruins, sacred catacombs, and epic tales of triumph and tragedy. This course takes students to Rome and Naples, with visits to archaeological treasures such as Pompeii, Herculaneum, Tivoli, and Ostia Antica.We’ll delve into the Roman obsession with death, exploring funerary monuments and burial practices, before diving into the spectacle of the gladiatorial games that captivated the masses. Students will walk the streets of ancient cities preserved by volcanic ash, study the grandeur of imperial palaces and Christian basilicas, including the Vatican, and trace the footsteps of emperors, gladiators, and everyday Romans, including ancient Christians.We’ll delve into the Roman obsession with death, exploring funerary monuments and burial practices, before diving into the spectacle of the gladiatorial games that captivated the masses. Students will walk the streets of ancient cities preserved by volcanic ash, study the grandeur of imperial palaces and Christian basilicas, including the Vatican, and trace the footsteps of emperors, gladiators, and everyday Romans, including ancient Christians.Total course cost: $4,650. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog.This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','','Humanities'),
(475,2025,25,752,'Adjunct Fall','Percussion Instruments','Thomas Mackey',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(476,2025,18,106,'4','Comparative Politics (W)','David Yamanishi',1,'POL',NULL,'This is an introductory course to the field of “comparative politics”, in which we will examine the world’s different political systems by contrasting and comparing the key aspects of their political systems, and by seeking generalizations about them. In this course, we will focus our attention on the three predominant types of political systems in the world: advanced industrial democracies, the current and former communist systems, and political systems in developing countries. Our principal theme will be the dilemmas inherent in moving toward democracy or in maintaining a stable democracy.As a step towards understanding the nature of these different political systems, we will undertake a discussion of the various ideological/theoretical explanations that help us draw comparisons and reach conclusions across the different countries. We will closely examine the structures and processes in certain countries that are particularly important “case studies” in various types of political systems. We will also discuss several global challenges for all the political systems in the 21st century in the final sections of the class.','POL 143','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Social Science'),
(477,2025,25,111,'6','Dynamic Earth','Emily Walsh',1,'GEO',NULL,'The earth as a dynamic body whose materials and structures are continually being modified by the interactions of the geological processes; considers interrelationships between geological processes and human activity. Fieldtrips as weather permits. Not open to students previously enrolled in GEO 114.','','Science'),
(478,2025,25,202,'6','Introduction to Film Studies','Katy Stavreva',1,'ENG',NULL,'An introduction to film as an art form, cultural practice, and institution. The class focuses on questions of film form and style (narrative, editing, sound, framing, mise-en-scène) and introduces students to concepts in film history and theory (e.g. national cinemas, periods and movements, institution, authorship, spectatorship, ideology, style, genre). Students develop a basic critical vocabulary and research practices for examining film. They apply their skills in oral and written analysis and interpretation to a wide range of films: old and new, local and global, mainstream and less familiar.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(479,2025,25,329,'1','Research Methods I','Christi Johnson',1,'KIN',NULL,'Introduction to the theoretical and practical concerns of kinesiology-related research. Emphasis is placed on developing an understanding of the historical and philosophical foundations of qualitative and quantitative approaches, reading and interpreting the literature, and research design. This course will culminate with the development of a formal research proposal and comprehensive literature review.','KIN 111, CPH 115, STA 201, KIN 207, KIN 208','Writing Intensive'),
(480,2025,25,512,'Adjunct Fall','Professional Practice','Ajit Chavan',0.25,'CSC',NULL,'Each student will gain experience in the iterative development of software through all stages of development, in presentations of a project to their peers, and in the review of their peers’ projects. Success will require application of knowledge and skills acquired in several core and elective courses. This practice solving problems like those encountered in industry and advanced study will prepare students for the challenges and opportunities that await them after graduation. Students should consult with an advisor in the department before beginning the course. In this course, students should plan on improving a project begun and substantially completed in another course. That other course may be taken concurrently. The course involves meeting twice each term for a total of 12 hours per semester and approximately 24 hours of work outside of class. Is repeatable once for credit.','CSC 140, CSC 144, CSC 218, CSC 301',''),
(481,2025,25,514,'Adjunct Fall','Life Drawing','Alex McKenzie',0.25,'ART',NULL,'No altenative grade option.','',''),
(482,2025,25,101,'7','Sociological Thinking','Mary Olson',1,'SOC',NULL,'Do you wonder why people do the things they do?  Why society works as it does?  Ever think the world is “unfair”?  Sociologists study people in the world, looking at patterns, at differences, at inequalities.  Thinking sociologically is like “entering a new and unfamiliar society--one in which things are no longer what they seem.”  It creates “culture shock without geographical displacement.”  This course requires us to look at society with a new perspective, to question our taken-for-granted assumptions, to investigate people\'s actions, and to explore the organization of society.  It provides a basis for being engaged citizens, thinking about social alternatives, and imagining possibilities for social justice. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(483,2025,25,322,'6','Evolution','Rebecca Richtsmeier-Ross, Isaac Winkler',1,'BIO',NULL,'Evolution is the unifying theory of biology and provides a framework for understanding the natural world. This course introduces students to the principles of evolution, emphasizing modern evolutionary biology, evidence, and hypothesis testing methods.','BIO 141, BIO 142','Science'),
(484,2025,25,275,'2','Topics: Contemporary Creative Nonfiction','Scott Morris',1,'ENG',NULL,'Creative nonfiction mixes the world of researched, factual writing with literary style, blending storytelling with critical analysis, to produce writing that is both entertaining and informative. In this class, we will especially focus on writing about the intersection of personal and professional or political issues: how writing can itself be a form of community building or resistance, of personal identity or professional persona, all while mingling research and personal experience. Together, we’ll analyze and appreciate how nonfiction writers navigate complex versions of their selves and the world. This is a literature course at its heart, but we’ll also be immersed in creative projects with writing exercises, drafting, revision, and thoughtful peer engagement, we’ll have the chance to develop our own writing voices in a complex conversation. ','ENG 201, ENG 202, ENG 215, ENG 225','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(485,2025,20,111,'1','How Do We Know What We Know? FYS','Chris Hoklotubbe',1,'INT',NULL,'This common first year seminar explores how we know what we know and the various ways and conventions by which we communicate knowledge. For example, how do we take in and evaluate information? How do our brains make deliberate and/or rapid decisions? How does our knowledge both individually and societally change over time? What does it mean to know something? How do we consider perspectives different from our own? Learning requires raising questions that stem from reasoning, curiosity, and empathy. Through questioning, we become informed citizens and scholars. Through careful reading, creative and critical thinking, speaking and writing, we will engage with a variety of texts from many genres and disciplinary perspectives. Your instructor will serve as a guide along this path by encouraging you to consider different perspectives on and ways of knowing as you start to identify areas for your own growth as a college student.','',''),
(486,2025,18,115,'3','Basic Acting','Caroline Price',1,'THE',NULL,'Study and practice in the essentials of the art and craft of acting. Emphasis will be given to observation, ensemble work, and character development, and all will be explored through scene and monologue study, class activities and performances, and paper/presentation assignments.','','Fine Arts'),
(487,2025,25,751,'Adjunct Fall','Scenery and Props SISTERS','Shawn Ketchum Johnson',0.25,'THE',NULL,'This course satisfies the following gen. ed. requirement(s):','','Fine Arts'),
(488,2025,15,220,'7','Tpc:Gallery Hopping as Artistic Research','Brooks Cashbaugh',1,'ART',170,'In this course, students will explore the world of contemporary art and relate this research back to their individual art practices. We will engage in virtual and in-person “gallery hopping” (visiting a number of galleries in quick succession) to view a broad spectrum of contemporary visual art. The goal of this class is to equip students with a rich understanding of current trends in the field of contemporary art and respond creatively. In this course, students will embark on a series of virtual “gallery walks,” where we collectively explore contemporary art galleries in New York City and Los Angeles remotely. We will expand on this with presentations from visiting speakers, videos, and critical theory that generate classroom conversations. At the end of each week, students will be given prompts for studio assignments to produce a work or works of art that incorporate elements of their research. Students make multiple trips to Iowa City to visit the Stanley Museum of Art, Public Space One, and the University of Iowa’s Galleries. Some materials will be provided in class, but students will have the flexibility to work with materials of their own choosing. There will be a course fee of $170 to cover the cost of some art materials and fees for visiting speakers.','ART 103, ART 104, ART 110, ART 115, ART 200','None'),
(489,2025,25,236,'6','Differential Equations','Fabian Candelaria',1,'MAT',NULL,'This course is about how to predict the future. Mathematical modeling with differential equations, initial value problems and their approximate solutions, systems of differential equations, qualitative solutions, stability analysis and an introduction to chaos, and Laplace transforms.','MAT 122, MAT 221',NULL),
(490,2025,25,334,'4','19th C: Jane Austen & her Afterlives','Katie Sagal',1,'ENG',NULL,'Jane Austen is one of the most beloved English novelists of all time, a bestseller in her own day and the inspiration for countless of fans, writers, artists, and filmmakers. In this course, we will connect some of Austen’s original novels (Pride and Prejudice and Sense and Sensibility) with the legacy they inspired in subsequent generations of creative activity—from twenty-first-century fan fiction, to works that present the story from a different perspective (Longbourn (2013), by Jo Baker), speculative reinterpretations (Sense and Sensibility and Sea Monsters (2009) by Ben H. White and The Scandalous Confessions of Lydia Bennett, Witch (2023) by Melinda Taub), and even films including the treasured BBC original and Pride + Prejudice + Zombies (2016). Given Austen’s enduring popularity in pop culture, we will also study tv shows influenced by her world including the Bridgerton series, new media mashups like the web series “Welcome to Sanditon,”and selected video and board games. This course will also encourage students to invest their own creative energies in the world of Jane Austen, pairing rigorous academic research and discussion with creative writing, art, and/or filmmaking.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, ENG 201, ENG 215, ENG 225','Humanities'),
(491,2025,25,330,'8','Introduction to Bioinformatics','Lauren Jepsen',1,'CSC',NULL,'Bioinformatics is the application of computational approaches to biological problems. This fast-growing field is becoming essential to biomedical research. This course will provide students with an introduction to the algorithms, tools, and computational methods used to analyze biological data. In this class, we will introduce many of the areas of study within the field of bioinformatics, including genomics, proteomics, structural bioinformatics and statistics. Students who take this course will leave with the ability to analyze data in python and R, search databases, perform sequence alignments, and use online tools to analyze genomic data.','CSC 140',NULL),
(492,2025,20,102,'8','Beginning Latin II','John Gruber-Miller',1,'LAT',NULL,'Introduction to the language of ancient Rome, its empire, the middle ages, and the early modern world. Students will learn the essentials of grammar, vocabulary, and Roman history and culture through reading, speaking, and writing Latin; increase English vocabulary through Latin derivatives; and read selections from Latin writers from different eras. Offered two out of every three years.','LAT 101','Language'),
(493,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Spring','Oboe: Woodwind Instruments','Lisa Ryoo',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(494,2025,25,277,'4','Topics: Arts Diaspora: Africans and Jews','Michael Feinberg',1,'ART',NULL,'This class investigates artists of African and Jewish descent during the eighteenth and\r\nnineteenth centuries. By exploring the artistic exchanges and shared histories between\r\nthese two minoritarian populations, students will analyze what it means to live in the\r\ndiaspora. Besides examining actual artworks, the class will also examine the problems\r\nassociated with collecting and exhibiting African and Jewish art.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(495,2025,25,513,'Adjunct Fall','Advanced Athletic Traning Practicum(1/2)','Kristi Meyer',0.5,'KIN',NULL,'Provides an advanced supervised practical experience in the prevention, evaluation, treatment, management, and rehabilitation of athletic injuries and illness. Participation in the administrative aspects of an athletic training program. May be taken over multiple terms. Maximum number of credits allowed: 2 credits. (1/2 credit per enrollment)','Must have at least one year experience as a Cornell Sports Medicine Assistant.','CR'),
(496,2025,24,201,'7','Statistical Methods I','Tyler George',1,'STA',NULL,'Elementary study of the science of data. Data collection, descriptive statistics, estimation, and hypothesis testing as applied to one- and two-variable problems.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100','Mathematics, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(497,2025,25,271,'2','Video Games as Literature','Katie Sagal',1,'ENG',NULL,'As any avid gamer knows, the best games are the ones that offer us something beyond sexy graphics and exciting special effects. Whether you prefer isometric ARPGs, realistic FPS, or indie platformers with quirky characters, the reason we come back to play for hundreds of hours boils down to worldbuilding. The skills, weapons, armor, and quest items for each playable character have more of an impact on gameplay and on our experience of the game if they link in meaningful ways to that character and their backstory. For those who love an immersive gaming experience, the overarching narrative of the world itself can make a huge difference in continuing to entice our engagement. In this class, we’re going to combine significant amounts of gameplay with thought-provoking readings and casual writing projects to delve into how and why we can value the literary aspects of video games. We will cover topics ranging from what it means to be human, where our fears come from, or what kinds of bodies are valued to philosophical questions like the significance of choice, fate vs free will, and the ethics of violence. In doing so, we’ll also read a collection of short stories to draw direct comparisons between more typically “literary” forms of storytelling and games.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(498,2025,15,283,'7','Musical Theatre Dance','Amy Simonson',1,'THE',NULL,'Musical Theater is defined as a form of theatrical performance that combines song, acting, and dance.  This course is designed for students interested in increased technical growth, in addition to enhancing qualities of performance through the practical study of musical theater dance.  Technical components of this course will include warm-up, diagonal exercises, and center combinations.  Students will gain a greater understanding of this genre through readings, discussions, video viewing, and written analysis. ','','Fine Arts'),
(499,2025,25,792,'Adjunct Spring','Saxophone: Woodwind Instruments','Ryan Smith',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(500,2025,25,326,'1','Managerial Economics','A\'amer Farooqi',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course applies formal tools of microeconomics to decision-making problems facing management. We will implement the ideas of supply, demand, elasticity, production and cost functions. Special emphasis will be placed on the statistical tools involved in demand forecasting and on a variety of pricing strategies. The course is built around a series of case studies produced by the Harvard Business School.','ECB 102','Social Science'),
(501,2025,25,771,'Adjunct Spring','Viola: String Instruments','Michelle Bennett',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(502,2025,25,212,'4','Sports and American Society','Rebecca Wines',1,'KIN',NULL,'Exploration of the impact of amateur and professional sports on the American way of life. Sample topics include women in sports, sports as the African-American community, sports as big business, and the relationship between sport and education. Readings reflecting a variety of viewpoints about the role of sports in American society will be selected from contemporary literature.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive, Writing Encounter'),
(503,2025,25,151,'8','Financial Accounting','Huan Cai',1,'ECB',NULL,'This course provides guidance in how to use accounting reports for financial analysis.  The primary objective of this course is to understand and analyze financial statements including Balance Sheet, Income Statement, Statement of Cash Flows, and Statement of Retained Earnings. Objectives of financial accounting rather than bookkeeping techniques.','','Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(504,2025,25,772,'Adjunct Fall','Bass: String Instruments','Derek Barnes',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(505,2025,99,712,'Adjunct Fall','Choir','Christopher Nakielski',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(506,2025,15,242,'2','Painting','Brooks Cashbaugh',1,'ART',215,'This course is an introduction to the technical, analytical and theoretical skills related to contemporary painting. Students will work with acrylic paint to develop a thorough understanding of image construction through color and mark-making. While perceptual painting is a major component of the class, varied methods of paint application, sensitivity to color and critical analysis of one’s own work are also stressed. Working with still life, landscape, human figures and abstraction, students will learn a wide variety of technical painting skills and also bolster their visual literacy and critical reasoning skills. Course format consists primarily of studio work. The course instructor provides guidance through lecture, demonstration, individual feedback and critique. Grading is based on willingness to experiment and take chances, time invested in the work, participation in class critiques, improvement throughout the block and implementation of concepts covered in class (regardless of student’s skill level). The course work will require some written work.  No alternative grade option.  [SA] This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $215 per student.','ART 103, ART 104, ART 200, ART 115','Fine Arts'),
(507,2025,18,314,'4','Methods of Elementary Mathematics','Corrine Neville',1,'EDU',NULL,'Current elementary school methods of instruction, lesson planning, computer applications, student assessment, and classroom management. Thirty hours of observation-practicum in the schools. Students must provide their own transportation. This course must be taken PRIOR to student teaching. No alternative grade option. This course requires an in-person practicum experience at the school. Students doing online learning are not eligible to take this course.','EDU 205, EDU 215, EDU 230, EDU 240','No course types found'),
(508,2025,25,253,'3','Managerial Accounting','Santhi Hejeebu, Heidi Hansel',1,'ECB',NULL,'Continuation of ECB 151. Application of accounting data to management decisions. Alternate years.','ECB 102, ECB 151',NULL),
(509,2025,25,111,'4','Introduction to Philosophy','Casey Scott',1,'PHI',NULL,'Problems of philosophy as they are discussed in the writings of major philosophers, including such topics as the nature of reality, problems with knowledge, morality, and the rationality of religious belief. Designed for first-year students and sophomores.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(510,2025,15,107,'6','Stagecraft','Scott Olinger, Shawn Ketchum Johnson',1,'THE',NULL,'Introduction to methods and materials of building theatrical scenery for production. Students are required to help build scenery for upcoming Theatre Department productions through lab work, utilizing methods learned in classroom component. Stage lighting instruction covers basic electrical theory, functions and properties of light, and hanging and focusing of various theatrical lighting fixtures.','','Fine Arts'),
(511,2025,25,502,'Adjunct Fall','Capstone Portfolio','Rebecca Wines',0.25,'FRE',NULL,'This adjunct course, supervised by a French professor, is required for all French majors. Students must meet with the professor as soon as they decide on a French major to discuss the expectations and process of the senior capstone portfolio and begin collecting artifacts from their French courses. Final portfolio compilation--including revising previous projects, writing new reflective pieces, and self-assessing competencies--will be completed during the spring semester of the student’s senior year, and will culminate in a polished, reflective, and synthetic collection of artifacts from previous French courses as well as assignments completed during this course. Course meetings are mandatory and will total approximately 3-4 hours per block; independent work outside of class meetings is expected.  During class time, students may workshop their assignments, participate in group conversations, and/or conduct self-assessment of skills. Pass/Fail only.  No alternate grade option.  Quarter (.25) credit course.','Senior standing, permission of instructor','Pass/Fail only, No alternate grade option, Quarter (.25) credit course'),
(512,2025,25,252,'6','Topics: American Political Behavior','Megan Goldberg',1,'POL',NULL,'This course examines a broad subfield of American politics known as \"political behavior.\" In this course, we will turn our attention away, in some respects, from the institutions that make up our government, and towards the people who are governed by those institutions. At the highest level, this course will dive into how people develop beliefs about politics, how they act on those beliefs, and how patterns in political behavior enhance or undermine democracy. We will ask what the role of public opinion should be in a democracy as well, and how the US compares to that standard.To answer those big questions, we will start by learning how to rigorously measure public opinion, how individuals form their opinions and beliefs, the many influences on their beliefs, and the role public opinion plays in policymaking. Throughout exploring these concepts, we will investigate actual data from public opinion surveys, the bread and butter of how we understand political behavior.','','Social Science'),
(513,2025,25,120,'6','The Holocaust','Tyler Carrington',1,'GER',NULL,'This course will examine the Holocaust from the perspective of social, cultural, and emotional history. We will seek to understand this genocide—its perpetrators and victims—in the context of modern German and European history, specifically interwar Germany and the rise of the Nazis, WWII, and long-standing anti-Semitism throughout Europe. Students will also interpret the eyewitness accounts and survivor memoirs that were produced in the wake of such evil and wrestle with some of the Holocaust’s most central and vexing questions: why did the Jews stay? Who was complicit? What did it mean to be a bystander? Where was God? This course will be taught in English and is designed for students of all backgrounds. Can count toward HIS major/minor.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(514,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Spring','Clarinet: Woodwind Instruments','Ronald Dieker',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(515,2025,25,791,'Adjunct Fall','Saxophone: Woodwind Instruments','Charlotte Leung-Brown',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(516,2025,17,104,'2','Studio Art Basics 3D','Stevie Delgado',1,'ART',65,'Introductory-level studio course exploring art elements, concepts, and history. Three versions are offered on a rotating basis: 2-D, 3-D, and Photo Imaging. Students are not allowed to repeat this course even if the medium is different. No alternative grade option.[SA]','','Fine Arts'),
(517,2025,15,388,'5','Seminar in Religion I: Perspectives FEE1','Steven Sacks',1,'REL',1250,'This course is devoted to advanced academic research, which will include development of relevant skills pertaining to the production of knowledge in the Humanities, including work with primary materials, mastery of discourse in a sub-discipline of expertise, writing and oral presentation.Alternate years, same year as REL 389. Total course cost: $1,250. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog.This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','','Humanities, Writing Intensive'),
(518,2025,200,102,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning Internship','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Civic engagement experiences are opportunities for students to contribute positively to society and connect to their local, national, and international communities. Civic engagement experiences should be grounded in civic and social responsibility and should emphasize collaboration with community stakeholders. Civic engagement experiences can be practiced through social activism, public scholarship, community advocacy, and direct service.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(519,2025,25,761,'Adjunct Fall','Piano','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(520,2025,25,420,'2','Student Teaching II','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements.','EDU 410','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(521,2025,25,368,'3','Adv Tpc: Viking Paganism & Gods of North','Steven Sacks',1,'REL',NULL,'This course will explore the existence and meaning of the Paganism in Viking as understood from the original sources and in our time, working from the literary and archeological elements forward into its present interpretation and understanding in the present day. We will pay particular attention to the place of pagan thinking in the West, and the means by which the contours of Norse paganism are informed by gender, sexuality and violence.','','Humanities'),
(522,2025,25,369,'8','Adv Topic: Psychology of Religion','Steven Sacks',1,'REL',NULL,'Religion is well known to contain the furthest reaches of abnormal psychology. This course will examine the relationship between psychological/neurological mental states and religion with an intercultural and comparative focus. Students will encounter a variety of literatures that examine the origins of and explanations for mythic and religious experiences, selfhood and the problem of \'other minds\'. ','','Humanities'),
(523,2025,25,772,'Adjunct Fall','Violin: String Instruments','Andrew Gentzsch',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(524,2025,25,231,'8','Engineering Statics','Danielle Grimes',1,'EGR',NULL,'Engineering Statics focuses on static forces on particles, bodies, and objects. Statics encompasses situations where bodies are at rest or moving at a constant velocity. Students will participate in problem solving and team designs using fundamental concepts and principles. Course topics include equilibrium, structural analysis, work and energy, friction, inertia, and momentum.','EGR 131,PHY 225',''),
(525,2025,25,213,'2','Topics in Philosophy: Bioethics','Genevieve Migely',1,'PHI',NULL,'This course will be an examination of the ethical issues involved in biomedicine and biomedical research. Fundamental moral questions of equality, justice, autonomy, and responsibility will be explored in issues such as healthcare practice, public health policies, life and death decisions, reproductive rights and responsibilities, genetic choices and manipulation, resource allocation, and research in the life sciences. How class, gender, race and ability factor into these controversial topics will also be highlighted. Case studies will be used to consider the issues from diverse ethical perspectives. This course would be beneficial for anyone interested in the healthcare profession, life sciences, and the critical moral concerns facing our society today.','','Humanities'),
(526,2025,18,115,'7','Basic Acting','Caroline Price',1,'THE',NULL,'Study and practice in the essentials of the art and craft of acting. Emphasis will be given to observation, ensemble work, and character development, and all will be explored through scene and monologue study, class activities and performances, and paper/presentation assignments.','','Fine Arts'),
(527,2025,25,142,'7','International Politics','Laura Story Johnson',1,'POL',NULL,'How and why states compete and cooperate internationally. Addresses concepts such as the balance of power between states, collective security through treaties and international organizations, nuclear deterrence, and the growing influence of non-Western states. Typically includes historical and current case studies. ','','Social Science, International Relations & Comparative Government, Writing Encounter'),
(528,2025,25,792,'Adjunct Fall','Oboe: Woodwind Instruments','Lisa Ryoo',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(529,2025,25,430,'3','Student Teaching III','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. Prerequisites: All 200- and 300-level Education courses and approval of the Education Department.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','EDU 420','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(530,2025,25,104,'7','Modern Europe and Its Critics','Jonathon Dreeze',1,'HIS',NULL,'The course will examine the fundamental events and processes in European politics, war, economics, culture, and society from the eighteenth century to the present. We will attempt to explain the origins of the contemporary world; how Europeans and the European world have arrived at where they are today. We will also strive to understand how Europeans lived and gave meaning to their lives in the “modern” era. The course is both topically and chronologically organized and emphasizes the common characteristics of European civilization rather than specific national histories. It traces threads of continuity while also examining the vast changes experienced by European society in the past 250 years. We will focus on particular cases that illustrate important patterns of change and conflict that have shaped the European world as we know it now. In doing so we will also examine how the idea of Western Civilization has changed over the centuries and what it means today in the early 21st century. No alternate grade option. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive, Writing Encounter'),
(531,2025,25,121,'2','Chemical Principles I','Andrea Dunn, Harmeet Bhoday',1,'CHE',NULL,'Fundamental concepts of chemistry, mole concept, energy, theories of the atom and the chemical bond, and molecular geometry. This course is intended primarily for those considering a major in science. CHE 121 utilizes concepts from high school algebra I and II.','','Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(532,2025,25,144,'8','Object-Oriented Programming','Ajit Chavan',1,'CSC',NULL,'Disciplined design, coding, and testing of substantial programs. Specification of relationships among components of a program using composition and inheritance. Reading, discussion, and writing about developments in computer science and the software industry.','CSC 140','Science, Writing Encounter'),
(533,2025,20,103,'5','Beginning German III','Ulrike Carlson',1,'GER',NULL,'Introduction to speaking, reading, writing and listening comprehension in German.  Facility in speaking and understanding spoken German is stressed. Readings emphasize culture, literature and contemporary life in the German-speaking countries.','GER 102','Language'),
(534,2025,25,111,'4','Dynamic Earth','Rhawn Denniston',1,'GEO',NULL,'The earth as a dynamic body whose materials and structures are continually being modified by the interactions of the geological processes; considers interrelationships between geological processes and human activity. Fieldtrips as weather permits. Not open to students previously enrolled in GEO 114.','GEO 114','Science'),
(535,2025,25,504,'Adjunct Fall','Algebra Essentials for Calculus','Fabian Candelaria',0.25,'MAT',NULL,'This quarter credit adjunct course supports students in developing the necessary strategies and reasoning skills needed to succeed in the MAT119-120 sequence.  Students will meet with the instructor in one 2 hour session each of the first three weeks of three consecutive blocks in a semester, and will have between one and one quarter and one and a half hours of work for each hour of class meetings, for a total of between 40.5 and 45 work hours. Topics include but are not limited to real and complex numbers; algebra foundations; polynomials and factoring; rational exponents; roots and radicals; linear equations and inequalities; quadratic equations; and graphing. Each block will include individual meetings with students to assess their current level and diagnose issues.','','CR'),
(536,2025,20,200,'1','Petroleum (SYS)','Charley Liberko, Andrea Dunn',1,'CHE',NULL,'One could make a case that besides water and blood, there is no liquid more critical to our survival in the modern world than petroleum.  While most of us are familiar with its importance as a source of fuel, it is easy to overlook its importance in producing the materials necessary to feed and clothe the world, and to provide anything beyond the crudest of healthcare.  Indeed, no understanding of modern history, politics, or economics is complete without some basic understanding of petroleum and its influence.  In this course, we will explore the complexity of petroleum as a material substance and the many ways it influences our lives. Only open to sophomores.','','Sophomore Year Seminar (SYS), Science'),
(537,2025,25,221,'5','Trials & Transitions of the Renaissance','Michelle Herder',1,'HIS',NULL,'This course explores the political, social, and religious changes of the Renaissance period (roughly, 1400-1600) through immersive simulations in which students adopt the personas of historical individuals. Topics may include Florentine politics, the Reformation Parliament called by Henry VIII, and others.','','Humanities'),
(538,2025,99,713,'Adjunct Fall','Jazz Ensemble','Benjamin Laur',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(539,2025,18,323,'2','International Economics Seminar','A\'amer Farooqi',1,'ECB',NULL,'Theory of international specialization and world trade, the institutions and mechanisms of world trade and payments, and major policy issues of concern to both industrial and developing economies. Course may be taught overseas in alternate years. When taught in Argentina the course focuses on the political economy of the country.   Argentina’s economic and business performance and problems will be studied in the context of its unique history and political system.','ECB 101','Social Science'),
(540,2025,25,751,'Adjunct Spring','Percussion Instruments','Virginia Armstrong',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(541,2025,25,251,'3','Sporting Identities (in English)','Rebecca Wines',1,'FRE',NULL,'How does soccer in Africa continue to show the impacts of colonization? How has sports-related migration impacted local and national teams? How does a national team’s roster affect ideas about a country’s identity? How can sports reinforce or disrupt gender performances? To begin to answer these questions, we will explore the intersections between sports and identities in places where French is spoken, giving special attention to the constructions of social categories such as gender, race, class, and sexuality. Examining a variety of literary and cultural texts, dating from the late 19th century to the present, we will investigate how and why sports have cultural meaning. Topics may include hockey in Québec, cycling’s Tour de France, and/or laamb (traditional Senegalese wrestling). No prior knowledge of sports or French is required. This course will be taught in English.This course may be counted as an elective for the FRE major/minor, the KIN major/minor and the GSS major/minor.','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, FRE 106','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive, Writing Encounter'),
(542,2025,25,111,'7','Introduction to Philosophy','Casey Scott',1,'PHI',NULL,'Problems of philosophy as they are discussed in the writings of major philosophers, including such topics as the nature of reality, problems with knowledge, morality, and the rationality of religious belief. Designed for first-year students and sophomores.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(543,2025,25,138,'2','Introduction to Physics','Danielle Grimes',1,'PHY',NULL,'This class is intended to be an introduction to physics for students who want to pursue an engineering or physics major, but who had limited or no experience with physics in high school.  In this class, we will study fundamental concepts in physics that are necessary for an engineering major. The class will use guided inquiry, hands-on activities, quantitative analysis, and mathematical analysis.  In addition to learning physics concepts, students will develop and practice skills in teamwork, written and verbal communication, and algebra and trigonometry. Students should have completed two years of high school algebra, including trigonometry.','','Science, Quantitative Reasoning Intensive'),
(544,2025,25,732,'Adjunct Fall','Trombone: Brass Instruments','Drew Bonner',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(545,2025,50,0,'4','Pending Individual Project','Registrar Staff',1,'PROJ',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, individual project. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the individual project block.','',''),
(546,2025,25,127,'3','Gods & War in Viking Civilization','Steven Sacks',1,'REL',NULL,'This course will explore the pagan civilization of the Vikings as understood from the original sources and in our time, and the means by which Norse culture was informed by - and is interpreted with - gender, sexuality and violence.','','Humanities'),
(547,2025,25,215,'8','Botany','Rebecca Richtsmeier-Ross, Isaac Winkler',1,'BIO',NULL,'An introduction to the structure and diversity of plants from ecological and evolutionary perspectives, with an emphasis on field identification of flowering plants. By observing plants in natural and human-developed habitats and in the lab, students will become familiar with the major local plant families and their characteristics and gain awareness of the ecological importance of native and introduced plants in Iowa ecosystems. One or more field trips may extend beyond normal class hours.','BIO 142','Science'),
(548,2025,25,511,'Adjunct Spring','German Reading & Conversation Group','Tyler Carrington',0.25,'GER',NULL,'German Reading & Conversation Group','',''),
(549,2025,25,781,'Adjunct Spring','Voice','Benjamin Laur',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(550,2025,18,115,'1','Basic Acting','Caroline Price',1,'THE',NULL,'Study and practice in the essentials of the art and craft of acting. Emphasis will be given to observation, ensemble work, and character development, and all will be explored through scene and monologue study, class activities and performances, and paper/presentation assignments.','','Fine Arts'),
(551,2025,25,731,'Adjunct Fall','French Horn: Brass Instruments','Peter Kortenkamp',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(552,2025,25,361,'3','Saints and She-Devils','Chris Penn-Goetsch',1,'ART',NULL,'Examination of some of the most common depictions of women during the late Medieval and Renaissance periods, beginning with Eve and the Virgin Mary. Themes include popular images of the hag, the witch, and the prostitute as well as other depictions that demonstrate how man is led astray by feminine wiles and “the exotic other.” Comparisons between Judaism, Islam, and Christianity are addressed.  Readings span from the Bible and Thomas Aquinas to contemporary scholars in gender studies. This course also counts towards the GSS major. Alternate years.','GSS 171, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, ENG 111, ENG 106, FRE 106','Humanities, Writing Encounter, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(553,2025,25,335,'6','Advanced Inorganic Chemistry','Cindy Strong',1,'CHE',NULL,'Properties of inorganic compounds with emphasis on theories of bonding and the chemistry of coordination compounds. Not offered every year.','CHE 327','Science'),
(554,2025,18,510,'Adjunct Fall','Volunteer Income Tax Assistance Prog (1)','Santhi Hejeebu, Huan Cai',0.25,'ECB',NULL,'Volunteer Income Tax Assistance (VITA) is a national IRS sponsored program that provides free preparation of federal and state tax returns for households with income less than $60,000. To get well prepared as a certified volunteer at VITA during the tax season in the following spring, students in this course will receive 10 training sessions during Block 1-3 (each  including about 1 hour of self-study and 1 contact hour with the instructors). In  Block 4, students will have 2-3 training sessions from the United Way/ VITA (each for about 7 hours) in Cedar Rapids. The training prepares students for the IRS certification exams to prepare for the role of volunteer tax preparer.','',''),
(555,2025,18,218,'7','Art & Activistm of Journal as CrWr','Scott Morris',1,'ENG',20,'Journaling is unique among the creative arts because you are both the creator and the audience. This cyclical relationship of internal creation-appreciation allows journal and diary writing to create opportunities for serious reflection and serious art. In this class we’ll look at journaling through a variety of lenses: we’ll read and discuss several theorists ideas about the impact and possibilities that journals have. We’ll also do a wide range of journaling: traditional diary keeping, freewriting, and even playing solo RPG journaling games. Throughout the course, we’ll emphasize the multimodal possibilities of journaling, mixing handwriting, typed words, drawing, and collected ephemera like photographs, receipts, and collage. The class will culminate with each student creating a journaling artist statement that makes a case for your own journaling aesthetic and choices.','','Fine Arts'),
(556,2025,200,101,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Academic research experiences are opportunities for students to develop their understanding of professional methods and fields of study appropriate to a chosen discipline or proposed research question. The value of research for undergraduate students lies both in the intellectual development of the student and in the potential discovery of previously unknown information. Academic research experiences should therefore emphasize the development of disciplinary research skills and methodology; they should be substantial (in breadth, scope, maturity, and effort involved); and they should encourage students to engage with the planning, execution, and presentation of their research efforts.  In addition, sharing the results of one’s research is an important part of the research process, which calls upon the researcher to participate in a community of scholars. Research experiences therefore should be presented or published in some form.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(557,2025,25,203,'6','Logic and Critical Thinking','Genevieve Migely',1,'PHI',NULL,'The use of logic and critical thinking ought to equip us to recognize, avoid, and correct errors in our reasoning. We’ll consider what we have learned about reasoning from philosophy and from recent research in the cognitive sciences in order to better understand our tendencies to reason badly and to learn to reason better. We’ll discuss deductive reasoning, but more emphasis will be placed on inductive arguments, on assessing the probability of beliefs relative to the reasons we have for them, and on how the presentation of new evidence ought to affect those beliefs. So, we’ll be thinking about why we believe what we do, whether the reasons we have for beliefs makes them probable, and how to revise our beliefs in light of new evidence. Logic addresses one of our most significant human qualities, our rationality, and so remains at the core of the liberal arts.','','Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(558,2025,25,161,'3','Fundamentals of Psychological Science','Samantha Heiman',1,'PSY',NULL,'Scientific study of behavior. Topics may include learning, development, personality, perception, physiological bases of behavior, the behavior of individuals in groups, and abnormal behavior.','','Social Science'),
(559,2025,25,115,'6','Fundamentals of Public Health','Tori Barnes-Brus',1,'CPH',NULL,'This course introduces the interdisciplinary field and subfields of public health, such as epidemiology, community health organizations, public policy, and program planning. Students will explore the social, political, and environmental determinants of health, address institutions that shape health, and investigate how public health impacts the health of communities and larger populations. Topics such as health promotion, mental health, environmental health, maternal and child health, and control of chronic and infectious disease will be addressed. With a focus on health disparities and community health broadly, issues of difference, inequality, and discrimination will be integrated into class discussion, assignments, and hands-on activities.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(560,2025,25,511,'Adjunct Fall','Extended Research in Chemistry','Harmeet Bhoday',0.25,'CHE',NULL,'Extended Research in Chemistry','',''),
(561,2025,10,485,'1','Geological Research','Andrew Walters',1,'GEO',NULL,'Serves as the capstone for the geology major. Research on a subject or problem selected by the student and approved by the instructor, involving library and field or laboratory study. Comprehensive term paper. May be repeated once for credit. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Research. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Writing Intensive'),
(562,2025,15,249,'4','Trad Culture&Contemp Issues Japan FEE1','Tori Barnes-Brus, Erin Davis',1,'SOC',5250,'This off-campus course, taught in Japan, examines the interconnections between Japanese cultural traditions and contemporary social issues. A major goal of this course is to provide a broad introduction to Japanese culture and society and to explore the juxtaposition of traditional and popular culture.  Issues and public policies related to gender, national identity, and health and well-being will be emphasized. Initial sessions will provide an orientation to enduring historical and cultural foundations and values as well as contemporary issues that inform everyday life in Japan. While in Japan, class members will participate in a variety of activities and discussions; will complete field excursions to historical, cultural, educational, and religious settings; and will read materials relevant to these themes. Students will also explore contemporary culture by observing and interacting with Japanese citizens and hearing from guest lecturers. The course typically includes travel to and within the Kyoto-Osaka (Kansai), Kanazawa, Hiroshima, and Tokyo (Kanto) regions of Japan. This course may count toward the SOC, PSY, CPH, and RES major. Total course cost: $5,250. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog. This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','SOC 101, PSY 161, EST 123, GSS 171, JPN 102, ANT 101','Social Science'),
(563,2025,18,352,'3','Novel Writing (NaNoWriMo)','Rebecca Entel',1,'ENG',NULL,'National Novel Writing Month (NaNoWriMo) challenges writers to produce a draft of a novel in a single month’s time. This creative writing course will adopt some of the tenets of NaNoWriMo, privileging generation over revision at the early stages of the writing process and providing “structure, community, and encouragement.” In addition to producing a significant portion of a novel draft through ambitious daily word count goals, students will be introduced to the work of contemporary novelists; will reflect on the literary traditions influencing their novels; and will explore a variety of writing processes. Open to students with previous experience writing fiction and an idea for a novel to begin on day one.','ENG 215','Fine Arts, Writing Encounter'),
(564,2025,200,104,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning Research','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Global Connections experiences are opportunities for students to broaden their perspective and improving their intercultural literacy through engaging with people from a culture other than their own culture or immersing themselves in a culture different from their own.  Global Connections experiences should also deepen students’ understanding of the interconnectedness of the world and the range of political, social, cultural, and economic issues affecting cultures and interactions around the world.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(565,2025,25,511,'Adjunct Fall','Extended Research in Psychology','Steven Neese',0.25,'PSY',NULL,'Reading in depth on a topic of current interest and the pursuit of an empirical problem related to the topic. Must be taken over four consecutive terms. Maximum number of credits allowed: same as for PSY 485. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Research. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','CR'),
(566,2025,25,792,'Adjunct Spring','Clarinet: Woodwind Instruments','Ronald Dieker',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(567,2025,25,774,'Adjunct Fall','Guitar','Tom Nothnagle',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(568,2025,150,700,'1','Vacation','Registrar Staff',0,'VAC',NULL,'Vacation blocks are open to seniors who are on track to complete 31 credits by block 8 of their senior year.  Non seniors must petition for permission to take fewer than 4 blocks per semester. If the student is on track to have 31 credits by the end of their senior year, the petition will be approved and the student will be registered for a vacation block. Otherwise, the student must explain in the petition how they will make up the missed credit.','',''),
(569,2025,25,332,'4','Mechanics of Deformable Bodies','Derin Sherman',1,'EGR',NULL,'An introduction to the effects of forces on solid bodies. Structures will be analyzed under axial, shear, torsional, and bending loads.  Students learn to assess structures in terms of stress, strain, and deflection under the various types of loading. The course emphasizes individual and group problem-solving.  Students apply course concepts to build and evaluate their own structures during hands-on design projects. No Alternate Grade option.','EGR 331, MAT 122','None'),
(570,2025,25,317,'2','Reproductive Practices, Reproductive Pol','Tori Barnes-Brus',1,'SOC',NULL,'This course emphasizes the social construction of female reproductive processes and how culture and institutions shape our understandings and expectations of such processes. Addresses a variety of reproductive practices, experiences and ideologies. Discusses ideas about womanhood, motherhood, fatherhood, sexuality, eugenics, and reproductive freedom; investigates historical role and effect of the state, medical institutions, and women themselves as they struggle over, and shape such issues. The focus will be on the U.S., but we may also look at cases from other countries in order to examine our assumptions about reproductive practices and strategies. Alternate years. This course may count toward the SOC, CPH, GSS, and RES major. ','SOC 101, CPH 115, GSS 171','Social Science, Writing Encounter'),
(571,2025,99,715,'Adjunct Fall','Orchestra','Andrew Gentzsch',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option.','','Fine Arts'),
(572,2025,14,284,'3','Ballet Studio I','Amy Simonson',1,'THE',NULL,'Ballet is an intermediate level movement course which focuses on continued technical development and artistic growth by emphasizing alignment and execution of complex movement combinations and artistic investigation.','','Fine Arts'),
(573,2025,25,430,'3','Student Teaching III','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. Prerequisites: All 200- and 300-level Education courses and approval of the Education Department.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','EDU 420','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(574,2025,25,320,'7','Madrid: Pop of Culture','Alyssa Selmer',1,'SPA',NULL,'After the death of the dictator Francisco Franco in 1975, the country of Spain experienced a boom of liberation that expressed itself in numerous artistic forms.  This 300-level course will have Madrid as its focus as we trace the cultural, literary, and artistic productions produced in the 1980s.  The class will analyze novels, films, music, and plays produced by Madrid-born men and women of this generation. Offered every third year. ','SPA 311','Humanities'),
(575,2025,20,111,'1','How Do We Know What We Know? FYS','Todd Knoop',1,'INT',NULL,'This common first year seminar explores how we know what we know and the various ways and conventions by which we communicate knowledge. For example, how do we take in and evaluate information? How do our brains make deliberate and/or rapid decisions? How does our knowledge both individually and societally change over time? What does it mean to know something? How do we consider perspectives different from our own? Learning requires raising questions that stem from reasoning, curiosity, and empathy. Through questioning, we become informed citizens and scholars. Through careful reading, creative and critical thinking, speaking and writing, we will engage with a variety of texts from many genres and disciplinary perspectives. Your instructor will serve as a guide along this path by encouraging you to consider different perspectives on and ways of knowing as you start to identify areas for your own growth as a college student.','',''),
(576,2025,18,104,'3','Studio Art Basics 2D','Alex McKenzie',1,'ART',75,'Introductory-level studio art course exploring art elements, concepts, and history. Three versions are offered on a rotating basis: 2-D, 3-D, and Photo Imaging. Students are not allowed to repeat this course even if the medium is different. No alternative grade option.[SA] This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $75 per student.','','Fine Arts'),
(577,2025,24,122,'7','Chemical Principles II','Diane Gingerich Feil, Cindy Strong',1,'CHE',NULL,'Rates of chemical reactions, equilibrium, acids and bases, electrochemistry, and an introduction to thermodynamics. Reactions and properties of selected elements and their compounds.','CHE 121','Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(578,2025,25,141,'5','Foundations: Cellular Biology','Diane Gingerich Feil, Nicole Green',1,'BIO',NULL,'The course introduces students to the principles of cell structure, cell function and information transfer by emphasizing the investigative approach to biological questions. Students design, execute, and interpret research. Research topics will vary with each instructor. This course is a prerequisite for most upper-level Biology courses.','','Science'),
(579,2025,25,782,'Adjunct Spring','Voice','Benjamin Laur',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(580,2025,25,153,'3','Origins of the American Nation','Phil Lucas',1,'HIS',NULL,'From colonial origins through Reconstruction, with emphasis on the formation of local, sectional, and national communities. No alternative grade option. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Encounter'),
(581,2025,18,220,'8','Nature Writing','Glenn Freeman',1,'ENG',NULL,'A creative writing workshop focused on writing concerned with the environment and human relationships with the environment. Our focus will be on non-fiction and the lyric essay. Students will produce a range of creative works and will engage in thoughtful discussion and critique of peers’ work. We will also read widely in the tradition of environmental writers, including writers such as Rachel Carson, Aldo Leopold, Sigurd Olson, Annie Dillard, Barry Lopez, Terry Tempest Williams, and Gary Snyder to study techniques used by these writers. Offered in alternate or every third year.','','Fine Arts, Writing Intensive'),
(582,2025,25,331,'1','Engineering Materials','Niloofar Kamran',1,'EGR',NULL,'It\'s essential for engineers to understand the properties of materials used in designs: how materials behave under different environmental conditions, and how they fail.  Students will study the mechanical, electrical, optical, chemical, and physical properties of materials including metals, glass and ceramics, polymers and composites.  Changes in materials as a function of temperature are covered as well as stress and strain.  No Alternate Grade option.','CHE 121, EGR 231',''),
(583,2025,25,205,'8','Cell and Molecular Biology','Sherri-Lynn Putz, Nicole Green',1,'BIO',NULL,'Basic metabolism and organization of cells and intracellular organelles. Introduction to the structure and synthesis of biological macromolecules.','BIO 141, BIO 142, CHE 122, CHE 161','Science, Writing Encounter'),
(584,2025,20,487,'6','Senior Thesis','Michael Feinberg',1,'ART',NULL,'A substantial capstone project to be completed during the senior year. Studio majors conceive, create, and mount an exhibition of a new body of work. Art history majors research an art historical problem, write a research paper, prepare an abstract, and provide a public presentation of their work with the goal of creating an original contribution to the discipline. An oral defense is required for either major. No alternative grade option. The Studio Art section is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression. The Art History section is pre-approved for transcript notation in the Ingenuity in Action category, Research. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','ART 483, ART 392','Ingenuity in Action category, Creative Expression, Ingenuity in Action category, Research'),
(585,2025,25,511,'Adjunct Fall','Intro Athletic Training Practicum (1/4)','Kristi Meyer',0.25,'KIN',NULL,'Provides an introductory supervised practical experience in the prevention, evaluation, treatment, management, and rehabilitation of athletic injuries and illnesses.Participation in learning Cornell Sports Medicine Assistant competency skills including taping, wrapping, stretching, and emergency care. This course may not be repeated for credit.','','CR'),
(586,2025,25,771,'Adjunct Fall','Violin: String Instruments','Andrew Gentzsch',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(587,2025,25,230,'5','Exceptional Learner','Corrine Neville',1,'EDU',NULL,'An introduction to understanding the diversity of learners in K-12 classrooms and how differentiated teaching methods and materials are essential to create a more inclusive and equitable environment for all students. The major focus of the course will be identifying the strengths and challenges of students to increase engagement and raise achievement through varied approaches to teaching culturally and linguistically diverse learners and students with documented needs.  Not open to juniors and seniors without permission of instructor.  No alternate grade option.Fifteen practicum hours required in the schools. Personal transportation will be needed for two separate days in this course.','','Social Science'),
(588,2025,25,215,'3','Psychology of Sport','Christi Johnson',1,'KIN',NULL,'Theory and issues related to psychological aspects of competitive sport contexts. Personality and sport, attentional control, anxiety and performance, motivation and attributions, aggression in sport, and team cohesion. Intervention strategies for performance enhancement.','','Social Science, Writing Encounter'),
(589,2025,25,715,'Adjunct Spring','Literature in Action: Editing','Rebecca Entel',0.25,'ENG',NULL,'Serving in one of the supervisory positions for the English Department literary magazine Open Field: Managing Editor, Copyeditor, Literature Editor, Art Editor, Assistant Editor, Designer, Publicist. Participation must be supervised by a member of the Department and the work carried out within a single semester. May be repeated for credit. This course is pre-approved for transcript notation for Ingenuity in Action. To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','','Fine Arts, CR'),
(590,2025,25,420,'5','Student Teaching II','Elizabeth Globokar',0,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements. Prerequisites: All 200- and 300-level Education courses and approval of the Education Department.This course is pre-approved for transcript notation in Ingenuity in Action.  To participate and earn notation of completion on your transcript, please complete the Ingenuity in Action application.','EDU 410','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(591,2025,25,223,'8','Business Ethics','Genevieve Migely',1,'PHI',NULL,' This course will examine where and how one finds moral integrity in the practice of business. Fundamental moral questions of justice, equality, and responsibility will be explored in both individual and corporate moral accountability in everyday professional interactions, in business missions, in corporate culture, and in basic hiring and evaluation practices. The effects of business on society, on the global market and community, and the world at large will be viewed through a variety of moral perspectives. Case studies will be used to highlight ethics at work. ','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(592,2025,25,710,'Adjunct Spring','Advanced Jazz Improvisation','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.5,'MUS',NULL,'A continuation of MUS 215 Jazz Improvisation. Study and discussion of the various approaches to jazz improvisation. Focus will be on chord/scale relationships, advanced harmonic substitutions, stylistic considerations, solo analysis, and relationships between harmony, melody, and structure. Students will also begin learning important pieces in the basic jazz repertoire. May be repeated for credit. No alternate grade option.','',''),
(593,2025,50,0,'1','Pending Individual Project','Registrar Staff',1,'PROJ',NULL,'Used as a placeholder for a planned, but not finalized, individual project. Paperwork must be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office at least one week prior to the start of the individual project block.','',''),
(594,2025,25,331,'3','Elem Methods and Materials for Music Edu','Christopher Nakielski',1,'MUS',NULL,'Introduction to the music teaching profession with a focus pertaining solely on the elementary level (PreK-8). This course will emphasize student evaluation, planning, classroom management, and teaching strategies rooted in the pedagogical principles of Zoltan Kodaly, Carl Orff, and/or Eugene Dalcroze. Twenty-five hours of observation/practicum in music in the schools. Students will need to provide their own transportation to their public school practicum.No alternate grade option.','MUS 310',''),
(595,2025,18,106,'2','Sociology of Game Design and Culture (W)','Erin Davis',1,'SOC',NULL,'In this course, we will examine game design and gaming cultures through a sociological lens. Through socio-cultural and rhetorical analysis of texts, games, and your own gaming experiences, we will explore the elements and expectations of game design and gameplay; the cultural representations, interactional experiences, and boundary marking practices of inclusion and exclusion; and other social factors impacting game design and cultures. This course encourages students to understand the importance of audience, context, and genre, to be deliberate in their compositional choices, and to communicate effectively and meaningfully. Not open to students who have previously completed a First-Year Writing Course.','','First Year Writing Seminar (FYW), Social Science'),
(596,2025,16,328,'Adjunct Spring','Advanced Organic Chemistry','Charley Liberko, Andrea Dunn',1,'CHE',NULL,'Selected advanced topics of reaction mechanisms or syntheses of organic compounds. Not offered every year. ','CHE 327','Science'),
(597,2025,20,311,'4','Introduction to Textual Analysis','Juana New Gavidia',1,'SPA',NULL,'Development of reading strategies and skills needed for analyzing and understanding literary texts. Organized around a topic, literary genre, period, or major writer and chosen to meet the needs of students who are just beginning upper-level coursework in Spanish. Special attention given to vocabulary development and to the advanced grammar required for understanding literary/cultural texts. Required of all Spanish majors.','SPA 301, SPA 302, SPA 303','Humanities'),
(598,2025,25,135,'6','Ancient Egypt: Magic and Civilization','Steven Sacks',1,'REL',NULL,'This course will provide both an introduction to the religion and reception of Ancient Egypt and the essential issues of Ancient Near Eastern literature, culture and civilization from Late Antiquity to the Present.','','Humanities, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(599,2025,150,700,'6','Vacation','Registrar Staff',0,'VAC',NULL,'Vacation blocks are open to seniors who are on track to complete 31 credits by block 8 of their senior year.  Non seniors must petition for permission to take fewer than 4 blocks per semester. If the student is on track to have 31 credits by the end of their senior year, the petition will be approved and the student will be registered for a vacation block. Otherwise, the student must explain in the petition how they will make up the missed credit.','',''),
(600,2025,25,237,'5','Care and Prevention of Athletic Injuries','Frannie Malone',1,'KIN',35,'Prevention and treatment of athletic injuries, taping experience, understanding the principles of athletic training, and first aid and emergency care.This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $35 per student for CPR certification. Required of all students, even those who have been previously certified.','',''),
(601,2025,25,361,'6','Modern Poetry','Glenn Freeman',1,'ENG',NULL,'Poetic trends in the first half of the twentieth century. Poets may include Eliot, Stevens, Williams, Stein, Loy, Millay, Hughes, and H.D. ','ENG 111, WREQ, WRT 016, WRT 100, ENG 201, ENG 202, ENG 215','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
