(625,2025,25,703,'Adjunct Spring','Instrumental Techniques Brass','Drew Bonner',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'Development of basic performing techniques. Study and evaluation of procedures and materials for elementary and intermediate instrumental teaching. No alternate grade option.','',''),
(626,2025,99,701,'Adjunct Fall','Music Performance Seminar','Jama Stilwell',0,'MUS',NULL,'A semester-long program requiring attendance at a number of musical events. The number of required events changes from semester to semester. Students should contact the Department of Music each semester for details.','',''),
(627,2025,25,515,'Adjunct Fall','Literary Citizenship','Rebecca Entel',0.25,'ENG',NULL,'Attendance at a minimum number of literary arts events each semester (determined by the faculty), participation in a writing group or relevant student organization, film screenings, book arts workshops, and the production of reflective and/or creative work in response to those events will be required for credit. Majors are required to register for two semesters of the adjunct course (.25 credit per semester); semesters need not be consecutive. Students will participate in a minimum of 12.5 contact hours including events, workshops, and other pertinent meetings, and undertake a total of 37.75 total hours of work. Course is assessed as credit/no credit.','',''),
(628,2025,25,761,'Adjunct Spring','Piano','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(629,2025,25,334,'4','Traveling Economists China Seminar FEE1','Todd Knoop',1,'ECB',6150,'This course focuses on the economic, social, and cultural changes taking place in China today. We will talk with local experts in Chinese development and business, visit local Chinese firms and factories, have class exchanges with Chinese college students, travel to the two major economic powerhouse cities of China—Shanghai and Beijing—but also visit western, rural, and poorer parts of China that still define the lives of most Chinese today.  This course will also\r\n refine our abilities to think like economists by focusing on the ways that incentives shape behavior and determine of difference across people, cultures, societies, and countries over time. Offered every other year. Total course cost: $6,150. Total course cost may be reduced with InAct funding. Apply via the InAct portal by April 4, 2025. Non-refundable deposit of $150 is due on April 11, 2025 for all 2025-2026 off-campus courses. Students must be in good academic, disciplinary, and financial standing with the College at the time of registration and one month prior to the beginning of the course. Details of this policy are available in the Catalog.This is a preapproved InAct Off-Campus Study experience. To apply for Ingenuity in Action credit, you must fill out the OCS application in the InAct Portal prior to your course departure. Please note you can fulfill this step while applying for funding.','ECB 101','Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(630,2025,25,771,'Adjunct Spring','Violin: String Instruments','Andrew Gentzsch',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(631,2025,20,200,'1','Sustainability of Earth Resources (SYS)','Emily Walsh',1,'GEO',NULL,'An examination of the finite nature of Earth’s natural resources through the lens of sustainability. Second-year students will consider the role of global citizenship as they investigate real-world, sustainability issues surrounding Earth resources, such as fossil fuels, critical minerals, rock & mineral commodities, fresh water, land use, or global cropland. Only open to sophomores.  Credit  cannot be earned for both GEO 125 and GEO 200.','','Sophomore Year Seminar (SYS), Science'),
(632,2025,15,305,'5','Junior Seminar','Katy Stavreva',1,'ENG',NULL,'The junior seminar opens avenues to further professional and research opportunities for all English majors. Organized around a central public humanities project, this course offers students hands-on experience in public scholarship and community-oriented research and action. Students engage in professionalization opportunities such as meeting with alumni in pertinent fields and preparing polished documents for jobs, internships, graduate school, or other post-graduate opportunities. Career and further education exploration is a strong focus of this course. Finally, students will plan and declare their capstone in this course.','ENG 201, ENG 202, ENG 215, ENG 218, ENG 220, ENG 225, ENG 230, ENG 240, ENG 267, ENG 271, ENG 273, ENG 274, ENG 275, ENG 276, ENG 277, ENG 278, ENG 311, ENG 317, ENG 318, ENG 319, ENG 321, ENG 323, ENG 325, ENG 326, ENG 327, ENG 328, ENG 329, ENG 331, ENG 332, ENG 333, ENG 334, ENG 335, ENG 336, ENG 343, ENG 345, ENG 347, ENG 350, ENG 351, ENG 352, ENG 361, ENG 363, ENG 364, ENG 365, ENG 368, ENG 369, ENG 370, ENG 371, ENG 372, ENG 373, ENG 374, ENG 381, ENG 383','Humanities, Writing Intensive'),
(633,2025,15,219,'8','Contemporary Collage Methodologies','Mark Baker',1,'ART',60,'Studio course centered on the making, presenting, and analysis of two- and three-dimensional art made from found materials. Students will learn numerous techniques to manipulate, alter, and combine elements while looking at examples of historical and contemporary artists. This course has an additional materials fee of $60 per student.','ART 103, ART 104, ART 115, ART 200','Fine Arts'),
(634,2025,25,224,'7','Environmental Ethics','Megan Altman',1,'PHI',NULL,'Moral dilemmas associated with human populations, industrial productivity, a deteriorating environment, and generally, our treatment of the natural world. We will examine the role our conception of ourselves and our relation to the non-human world plays in our exploitation of the environment and its degradation.  We will consider alternatives to traditional “anthropocentric” ethics and discuss the possibility of living in ways consistent with both the protection of the environment and the well-being of all things of moral worth. Alternate years.','','Humanities'),
(635,2025,25,781,'Adjunct Spring','Voice','MUS Dept Chair Staff',0.25,'MUS',NULL,'No alternate grade option. Lesson Fees: Please note that students who are not music scholarship recipients ($3,000+) are responsible for paying a lesson fee. These fees are the same for lessons on secondary instruments.  Recipients of music scholarships will not be charged for lessons on their principal (scholarship audition) instrument.','','Fine Arts'),
(636,2025,18,104,'4','Studio Art Basics 2D','Alex McKenzie',1,'ART',75,'Introductory-level studio art course exploring art elements, concepts, and history. Three versions are offered on a rotating basis: 2-D, 3-D, and Photo Imaging. Students are not allowed to repeat this course even if the medium is different. No alternative grade option.[SA]This course has an additional materials fee of approximately $75 per student.','','Fine Arts'),
(637,2025,25,328,'2','Exercise Psychology & Comm/Behav Health','Noah Johnson',1,'KIN',NULL,'Examination of theory and current research regarding the promotion of health as related to physical activity; including psychological, social, community-based, policy, and cultural influences. Topics include psychological and emotional effects of exercise, barriers and facilitators for physical activity, factors in exercise avoidance, adoption, and adherence, cognitive, behavioral, social, and policy-oriented change strategies for exercise, and consideration of gender, ethnicity, and special needs populations.','KIN 111, CPH 115, BIO 208','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Encounter, Writing Encounter'),
