(692,2025,25,205,'2','Historical Foundations of Education','Sarah Doyle',1,'EDU',NULL,'This course explores the historical, sociological, and philosophical foundations of education. The class will draw upon the broad, theoretical issues of education through a variety of written and discussion-based activities. Particular attention is paid to curriculum theory, the civic and democratic mission of the common schools movement, Dewey and the Progressive Era of schooling, and the current social context of schools. Students are encouraged to critically analyze the purpose of schooling and to further develop their own philosophies of education through reflection and dialogue. No alternative grade option.Not open to juniors and seniors without the permission of instructor.','','Humanities, Writing Encounter'),
(693,2025,18,200,'1','Tradition and Innovation in Society(SYS)','James Martin',1,'MUS',NULL,'Tradition and Innovation in Society through the Arts and Humanities In this Second-Year-Seminar we will look at traditions and innovations/technologies with a critical eye, using moral philosophy, technology essays/critiques, music, literature/novel, films, and utopic and dystopic works and ideas. These approaches will provide lenses for our examinations. The organizing terms “tradition and innovation” are to be a helpful springboard that launches us into critical thinking, creative thinking, discussion, etc. The final outcome of this will be a Final Major Group Project that investigates and problematizes a particular question, topic, etc., proposes possible solutions, and presents this work: 1) in a final major paper, 2) in large Poster Form, 3) in a class presentation that includes your Poster and questions from the audience (our class), and 4) at the Final SYS Showcase, which will include the Poster, your describing your work to visitors, your answering of these visitors’ questions. Only open to sophomores. This course does not count as an elective toward any Music major or minor.','','Sophomore Year Seminar (SYS), Humanities'),
(694,2025,25,102,'8','Microeconomics','James Goodenberger',1,'ECB',NULL,'Basic microeconomic analysis of consumer choice, the business firm, and resource markets in labor, capital, and land. Analysis and critique of government policy in problem areas such as monopoly power and government regulations and expenditures. ','two years of algebra in high school','Social Science, Quantitative Reasoning Encounter'),
(695,2025,25,101,'6','Cultural Anthropology','Noah Johnson',1,'ANT',NULL,'The course provides a cross-cultural, critical perspective on human behavior and society.  The diversity of human cultures from nomadic food foragers to industrialized city dwellers is examined, and the implications of subsistence, social, economic, political, and religious systems for the lives of men and women are explored through readings, videos and lively discussions.  Students are provided with tools to more objectively compare other cultures with their own.  Emphasis on non-Western cultures. Not open to seniors without permission of the instructor.','','Social Science, Intercultural Literacy Intensive'),
(696,2025,25,503,'Adjunct Fall','Math for the Natural Sciences','Jessica Johanningmeier',0.25,'INT',NULL,'This course emphasizes the importance of quantitative literacy in the natural sciences. The course will provide instruction and practice in applying mathematical skills to solving problems in the natural sciences.  Students will meet with the instructor in three 1 – 1.5 hour sessions each of the first three weeks of three consecutive blocks in a semester, and will have approximately an hour of work for each hour of class meetings, for a total of 25 hours.  The course will focus on the following primary topic areas:  algebra and its application to solving problems, logarithms, unit conversions, scientific notation, calculator use and graphs.  Each block will include individual meetings with students to assess their current level and diagnose issues. Offered every first semester.','',''),
(697,2025,25,101,'7','Fundamentals of Music','Jama Stilwell',1,'MUS',NULL,'An introductory music theory exploration, this course begins with pitch and rhythm reading skills; leads to understanding of intervals, scales, keys, and chords; and culminates in development of basic skills in musical analysis and composition. Previous experience in reading music is recommended, but not required. Preparation for MUS 110.','','Fine Arts'),
(698,2025,25,410,'5','Student Teaching I','Elizabeth Globokar',1,'EDU',NULL,'A 14-week clinical teaching experience under the direction of Cornell faculty and certified K-12 school teachers in approved elementary or secondary schools, taken in conjunction with EDU 420 & EDU 430. Attendance at a bi-weekly evening seminar is required. These three courses (EDU410, 420, & 430) must be scheduled in consecutive terms during the senior year or during a fifth year. Required for a teaching certification recommendation in the State of Iowa. Students must provide their own transportation. EDU 440 may be required or taken as an option, specific student requests/requirements.','All 200- and 300-level Education courses, approval of the Education Department','CR, Teacher Preparation'),
(699,2025,200,104,'Experiential Learning','Experiential Learning Research','',0,'EXP',NULL,'Global Connections experiences are opportunities for students to broaden their perspective and improving their intercultural literacy through engaging with people from a culture other than their own culture or immersing themselves in a culture different from their own.  Global Connections experiences should also deepen students’ understanding of the interconnectedness of the world and the range of political, social, cultural, and economic issues affecting cultures and interactions around the world.','','Experiential Learning Requirement'),
(700,2025,16,245,'5','Laboratory Physics','Derin Sherman',1,'PHY',NULL,'In this course, students will learn important concepts in electricity, magnetism, and circuits by doing experiments.  This knowledge will help prepare them for more advanced courses in these topics.  Concepts include: charge, electric fields, electric potential, voltage, current, magnetic fields, magnetic forces, Faraday\'s law, capacitance, resistance, inductance, motors, generators, electrical energy and power. ','PHY 225',NULL),
